<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Floyd Excited, Nervous About Bulls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Like Phil Jackson had so many times before him,  
Tim Floyd walked onto the United Center floor a few steps behind 
Michael Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	Only this wasn't for pre-game introductions, this was to say  
goodbye. And as Floyd stood off to the side watching, he knew his 
job had just gotten much, much tougher. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was disappointed, just from our coaching staff's standpoint,  
because we all recognize the importance of what he could have meant 
to us this year in terms of wins and losses,'' Floyd said of how he 
felt when he learned Jordan was retiring. 
</P>
<P>
	``But happy. For a guy that brought a lot of happiness to a lot  
of other people, if that's what he wants to do, because he 
certainly went out on top. We had a real cordial exchange of best 
wishes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Six months after he joined the Chicago Bulls with the temporary  
title of director of basketball operations, Floyd is finally coach 
of the six-time NBA champions. But it's a far different team than 
the one Jackson left in June. The greatest player in the game is 
retired, and the rest of the Bulls are about to leave town. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd is left with four players, a grand tradition, plenty of  
questions and very, very big holes to fill. 
</P>
<P>
	``(I'm) excited, real excited, about the opportunity that's in  
front of me,'' he said Friday, shortly after being named Chicago's 
head coach. ``(But) it's going to be a very difficult task, and I 
don't know that anyone has been in this exact situation before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not likely. Floyd takes over the NBA's team of the 1990s -- six  
titles in eight years -- as a rookie. He's been very successful at 
the college level -- 243-130 and runner-up for The Associated Press' 
national coach of the year in 1995-96 -- but has never coached in 
the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	His toughest hurdle is Jordan's departure. Jordan openly mocked  
Floyd when he was touted as Jackson's successor, and he said he 
didn't want to play for anyone but Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	But Floyd doesn't think fans will hold him responsible for His  
Airness' retirement. He checked with one of Jordan's friends before 
taking the job, and was told to go ahead. He was told Jordan was 
burned out, mentally drained from the season and not sure he wanted 
to play basketball again, Jackson or no Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	And that's exactly what Jordan said when he retired Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't feel like that's an issue,'' Floyd said.  
</P>
<P>
	Besides, most fans' ire is directed at chairman Jerry Reinsdorf  
and general manager Jerry Krause right now. Floyd, with his warm, 
friendly, downhome personality, has won over the fans he's met so 
far, quick to smile and chat when he's out. 
</P>
<P>
	He refuses to take himself too seriously, joking about the  
challenges ahead. And he's not interested in making the Bulls ``Tim 
Floyd's team,'' saying he'll run the same systems Jackson did. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do recognize the tradition and I recognize what's at stake  
and I know there's a great deal at stake. But I'm looking forward 
to the task,'' he said. ``I still think this is an incredible 
opportunity for somebody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Make no mistake, though, Floyd knows exactly what he's in for.  
Six, golden championship trophies greet him every day when he goes 
to work, and title banners hang all over the Bulls' practice gym. 
</P>
<P>
	When he walked into the United Center last week, he couldn't  
help but feel butterflies. He doesn't expect them to go away 
anytime soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they weren't there, then I think there'd be something  
really wrong with me,'' he said. ``I've attended games in the 
United Center before as a spectator and I'm aware of the atmosphere 
that's generated and the electricity that's been in the building 
since it opened. 
</P>
<P>
	``You hope you can go out there and just not cheat the fans  
because you know how important this is to so many people.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
