<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pfizer Seeks Viagra Spray Patent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Pharmaceutical manufacturer Pfizer Inc.  
says it has filed for a patent on a nasal-spray version of its 
anti-impotence drug Viagra. 
</P>
<P>
	The company made the announcement Friday in response to two  
University of Kentucky researchers who claimed this week to have 
developed such a fast-acting spray. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're certainly not ready to speculate in terms of when we'll  
have a product out,'' said Pfizer spokeswoman Mariann Caprino. ``We 
are moving forward in terms of investigating this as a potential 
delivery system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer said the spray was developed and tested in England, but  
offered no other details. 
</P>
<P>
	The two UK College of Pharmacy professors, Lewis Dittert and  
Anwar Hussain, reported this week that the spray they've developed 
drops the time it takes Viagra to take effect from over an hour to 
five to 15 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Dittert released a statement Friday in response to Pfizer's  
claim that it also has a nasal version of Viagra in the works. 
</P>
<P>
	``They did not tell us they had a patent application in this  
area,'' Dittert said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
