<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grits'n Hard Toast Wins Holy Bull </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Grits'n Hard Toast closed with a rush to  
overtake Doneraile Court in the closing stretch to win Saturday's 
$100,000 Holy Bull Stakes at Gulfstream, the year's first major 
test for 3-year-olds. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a strong ride by Robbie Davis, Grits'n Hard Toast stood  
fourth entering the final furlong before chasing down the leaders. 
He finished the 1 1-16th miles in 1:46 1-5, returning $31.20, 
$10.20 and $5. 
</P>
<P>
	Doneraile Court, the 2-1 second choice, edged Mountain Range for  
second and paid $5.60 and $4. Mountain Range returned $3.60 to 
show. 
</P>
<P>
	Vicar, the 6-5 favorite, faded down the stretch to finish fifth  
in the seven-horse field. 
</P>
<P>
	The Holy Bull Stakes usually provides a showcase for Kentucky  
Derby hopefuls, but this year's field was not a strong one. 
</P>
<P>
	Grits'n Hard Toast won just two of six starts as a 2-year-old,  
finishing third in the Kentucky Jockey Club Stakes on Nov. 28 at 
Churchill Downs. The Kentucky-bred son of Bates Motel boosted his 
earnings to $137,547 with Saturday's win. 
</P>
<P>
	Doneraile Court opened a two-length lead turning down the  
backstretch, followed by Mountain Range, Stone Bridge and Vicar. 
Grits'n Hard Toast was next to last, 10 lengths off the pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Mountain Range moved within a length of the leader heading to  
the far turn, but Doneraile Court spurted to a three-length lead 
approaching the quarter pole. 
</P>
<P>
	Doneraile Court led Mountain Range by two lengths at the eighth  
pole before Grits'n Hard Toast began his big move. 
</P>
</TEXT>
