<DOCNO> APW19990116.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:09:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steve Francis Rises to Greatness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) -- Steve Francis has always found comfort  
on the basketball court. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether he was shooting at bent rims on playgrounds, in chilly  
junior high school gyms or a firehouse basement, Francis focused on 
putting the ball in the basket, not on the struggles of growing up. 
</P>
<P>
	His dedication has paid off. The skinny, 6-foot-3 guard now runs  
the show for fifth-ranked Maryland, using blurring quickness and 
acrobatic moves to break down defenses. He then scores or sets up 
teammates with pinpoint passes. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the best 1-on-1 player on the team, maybe in the  
country,'' Maryland center Obinna Ekezie said. 
</P>
<P>
	But it has not been easy for Francis to earn such praise. His  
life has been full of sadness. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 6 when his father abandoned the family and by age 10  
Francis was working summer jobs to ease the financial burden on his 
mother, Brenda. 
</P>
<P>
	School was also a struggle. Francis was academically ineligible  
to play as a freshman at Blair (Md.) High School, saw little action 
as a 5-foot-3 sophomore and missed his junior season with a broken 
ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	Then things got worse.  
</P>
<P>
	Francis dropped out of school during his senior year after his  
mother died of cancer at age 39. 
</P>
<P>
	``For six or seven months after that, I couldn't move,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Francis took refuge at a tiny firehouse gym that was also the  
home of an outreach program for youths. At about the same time he 
got a tattoo on his right arm -- a 4-inch cross with the words, ``In 
Memory'' on top and ``Brenda'' in the middle. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, the 20-year-old Francis rubs the tattoo each time he  
prepares to take a free throw for Maryland. After spending two 
years playing for junior college teams that never lost a 
regular-season game, he is enjoying success at the Division I 
level. 
</P>
<P>
	Francis leads Maryland in minutes, scoring and steals and is the  
main reason why the Terrapins are talking about reaching the Final 
Four for the first time. Instead of being burdened by the lofty 
expectations, Francis has carried himself as if he hasn't got a 
worry in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a reason for that. Steve had adversity in his life at  
an early age,'' Maryland coach Gary Williams said. ``I think you 
handle it two ways: One, you just quit and don't make anything out 
of yourself. Or like Steve, you become determined to go the other 
way and be something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even on those rare occasions when his game is off, the junior  
still gives NBA scouts and opposing coaches something to think 
about. 
</P>
<P>
	Francis went 3-for-14 from the field earlier this month in a  
home loss to Duke, but his whirling reverse layup in the first half 
was the most spectacular play of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love Steve Francis,'' Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski said. ``He  
looks like he can score every time he gets the ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe he can. But Francis has blended his game with that of his  
teammates, learning to play the point and shooting guard in order 
to mesh with a squad already deep with talent. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I came in here, a lot of people said, `He's going to be  
the one who's going to lead them to this or that.' I'm not trying 
to lead this team,'' Francis said. 
</P>
<P>
	But when the offense is struggling, the Terrapins look to  
Francis to make something happen. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time our offense breaks down he just creates something.  
That's the advantage we have over almost everyone else,'' Ekezie 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Francis may not be the team leader -- the three starting seniors  
have assumed that responsibility -- but he is the engine on a 
Maryland team that has been in the top 5 since the season began. 
</P>
<P>
	He is averaging 17 points per game and was impressive enough in  
his first dozen games to warrant selection as a candidate for the 
Wooden Award, presented annually to the nation's best college 
basketball player. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I've played well so far, but I can be a lot better,''  
he said. ``There is a lot of stuff that I need to work on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The big question around Maryland these days is whether Francis  
will round out his game at College Park next season or take a shot 
at the NBA, where he stands a good chance of being a lottery pick. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope Steve really enjoys this year and he helps us be a  
very good team,'' Williams said. ``Whatever happens after that 
happens.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
