<DOCNO> APW19990116.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> For Brazil's Poor, Life Stays Hard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil's decision to sharply  
devalue its currency was a shock to world markets but registered 
little more than a dull thud in the life of Paulo Januario's 
family. 
</P>
<P>
	``My son is 16 years old, where is he going to find work?''  
Januario, 41, a security guard on Rio's poor north side asked on 
Saturday. ``My problem isn't Brazil's economy, it's my own economy 
and how I cope with everyday life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Januario is among the two-thirds of Brazil's 160 million people  
earning up to 390 reals a month. It doesn't matter much to him that 
last week's devaluation means he earns 17 percent less in dollar 
terms -- $270 today as opposed to $325 a week ago. Like most 
Brazilians, he is unlikely to buy dollars as a hedge against 
inflation or to travel abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Brazil's decision to sharply devalue its currency could  
lead the government to adopt measures needed to heal the economy. 
If it can reduce 29-percent-a-month interest rates, the likelihood 
of creating jobs for people like Januario's son goes up. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the mountains in Rio's Ipanema district, the drop in the  
value of the currency has an immediate and painful impact on 
Brazil's small middle class. It reduces the buying power that sent 
record numbers of Brazilians traveling abroad in the past 4 1/2 years 
and created a boom in imported goods. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm earning the same money, but overnight it isn't going as  
far,'' said Ronaldo Maia. The 60-year-old judge sat in a travel 
agency waiting to buy an airplane ticket suddenly made more 
expensive because overseas fares in Brazil are quoted in U.S. 
dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Suzana Saldana, a professor at the Federal University of Rio de  
Janeiro, said her car payment -- also indexed to the dollar -- just 
jumped from 1,800 reals a month to 2,200 (roughly $1,500 before and 
after the devaluation). ``I haven't had my salary readjusted in 
four years and now my money is worth even less,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Down the street, a ``doleiro'' who buys and sells dollars on the  
illegal but largely tolerated parallel market, said business has 
tripled in the past week. His rates were 4 centavos better than 
bank rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1990s, Brazil's middle class purchased dollars to  
hedge their losses as inflation rose to around 2,700 percent a 
year, and the local currency was devalued at about the same rate. A 
1994 economic stabilization plan meant, for a time, that a dollar 
bought just 82 centavos to the real. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a time at the start of the real plan when I thought  
I'd have to go out of business, but now it's almost like old 
times,'' said the doleiro, who would only identify himself as 
Rodrigo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 01:52:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta's Young Defends Olympic Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- There was no bribery involved in Atlanta's  
Olympic bid for the 1996 Summer Games, former Atlanta mayor and 
United Nations ambassador Andrew Young said as the scandal 
involving payoffs for the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City 
widens. 
</P>
<P>
	Humanitarianism, not bribery, motivated Atlanta's assistance to  
Third World athletes and Olympic officials before and after the 
1996 Games, Young told The Atlanta Journal-Constitution in today's 
editions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Absolutely no money changed hands,'' he said of Atlanta's  
winning bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``We raised money, we raised it openly, we discussed it  
publicly. It's inconceivable to me that Atlanta (dealings), prior 
to the bid, could be conceived as a bribe to get the Olympics,'' he 
said in today's editions of the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the city was helping the less fortunate.  
</P>
<P>
	``You are expected to help people in need in the Olympic family,  
particularly if you come from a rich country such as this,'' said 
Young, who helped Billy Payne mastermind Atlanta's winning bid. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Olympic Committee asked 13 of its members to  
explain their actions in dealing with the bid committees in Salt 
Lake City and other cities. IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch 
said that nine cases could possibly be serious enough to lead to 
expulsion. 
</P>
<P>
	``After we bid (in 1990), people wanted us to help,'' Young  
said. ``And you can't have an operation that makes that much money 
and have poor people with nothing and them not ask for help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the president of Mozambique mentioned in 1991 that his  
country's runners weren't getting enough protein, Young said he 
helped organize a shipment of food and protein that was paid for by 
U.S. corporations. 
</P>
<P>
	He said when David Sikhulumi Sibandze, an IOC member from  
Swaziland, became ill on a visit to Atlanta during the bidding 
process, he was sent to a doctor and received free hospital tests 
after complaining of chest pains. 
</P>
<P>
	``We never did anything for anybody in a humanitarian way  
related to the Olympics that we hadn't done anyway and that we 
wouldn't do if the Olympics wren't involved,'' Young said. 
</P>
<P>
	Young served as an unpaid adviser to Salt Lake's successful bid  
for the 2002 Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
