<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A group of Protestant churches says the $2  
million cost of Pope John Paul II's visit to Mexico City later this 
month is proof that Roman Catholic leaders are removed from the 
struggles of the country's poor, a newspaper reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Adoniram Gaxiola, spokesman for the Secretariat of Public  
Relations for Evangelical Churches, also criticized plans to build 
a $7 million evangelical center at the Catholic Church's Basilica 
of Our Lady of Guadalupe in Mexico City. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is nothing but a fight by the Catholic Church to recover  
ground lost'' to other churches, the daily Reforma quoted Gaxiola 
as saying. ``But this already is an irreversible situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Papal Nuncio Justo Muller said the $2 million price tag for John  
Paul's Jan. 22-27 visit includes transportation, food and housing 
for the pope and his delegation, Reforma reported. A leading 
Mexican bank, Banamex, will cover the costs, which the church plans 
to pay back through the sale of medallions commemorating the trip. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Seventeen members of a special Chiapas state  
police force have been detained for allegedly shooting and wounding 
two young men suspected of embezzlement, the government news agency 
Notimex reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The members of the Special Unit Against Crime, including its  
chief, Pedro Martinez Tamayo, are accused of using unnecessary 
force against the two men early Friday, Notimex quoted state 
prosecutor Eduardo Montoya as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya said state officials were ensuring that the two young  
men, Raul Hernandez and Jose Damian, received medical care. 
</P>
<P>
	Notimex did not give details of the Friday shooting or the men's  
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexican police have seized 10,000 sea turtle  
eggs that apparently were stolen from coastal nesting grounds in 
the southern state of Oaxaca, a news report said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said two men were transporting the eggs along a highway  
in Oaxaca state early Friday and ran away when they saw the 
officers approaching them, the daily Reforma reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The men fled and police recovered seven sacks and three baskets  
containing the eggs, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexican law prohibits the harvesting of turtle eggs, which are a  
popular delicacy in some parts of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Countries in the Americas will accept  
the plan of Venezuela's president-elect to replace his country's 
constitution, provided it is done legally, U.S. Ambassador John 
Maisto said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Addressing state governors in the western city of Barquisimeto,  
Maisto said President-elect Hugo Chavez's plan should take place 
``within a democratic and constitutional framework'' and be ``the 
product of negotiations and consensus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez, 44, a former army paratrooper who led an unsuccessful  
coup attempt against Venezuela's democratically elected government 
in 1992, says a new constitution is needed to overhaul what he says 
is the country's antiquated political system. He takes office on 
Feb. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States had long been wary of Chavez, denying him a  
tourist visa because of his coup attempt. But after Chavez won a 
landslide victory in Dec. 6 presidential elections, the Clinton 
administration congratulated him and urged him to respect 
democracy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
