<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 21:12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Borden, Chow Take Honors at Reese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Amanda Borden and Amy Chow, two of the  
``Magnificent Seven'' women's team that won the Olympic gold in 
1996, took the women's top honors Saturday at the Reese's 
Gymnastics Cup, the sport's annual night of lighthearted 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Borden and Chow wrapped up first place with enthusiastic floor  
exercise routines. Borden, the 1996 Olympic team captain and now 
team manager of the Arizona State University gymnastics squad, 
performed to a Michael Jackson medley. Chow, a sophomore pre-med 
student at Stanford, did an acrobatic ``Freeze Frame'' 
presentation. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Waller, 30-year-old former national champion, teamed with  
2000 Olympic hopeful Blaine Wilson, 24, to win the men's event. 
</P>
<P>
	Jessica Davis and Natalie Lacuesta were the rhythmic winners.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is my favorite part about gymnastics, being able to  
perform for people and having a good time,'' Borden said. ``For 
people like me who really aren't into serious competition anymore, 
this is what I love to do. This is the only reason I continue to do 
gymnastics is because it's fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a night for entertainment, not intense competition, with  
John Macready doing a floor exercise in tuxedo, Jason Gatson 
blindfolded on the horizontal bar and Kristie Phillips in knee-high 
pink boots on the balance beam. 
</P>
<P>
	``Regular gymnastics is also to entertain the crowd, but this  
also gets the crowd involved,'' Wilson said. ``You can pull them 
out of their seats and get them down on the floor almost. You're 
still a little nervous, though. You don't want to fall on your 
face.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody did, unless it was on purpose as part of the show.  
</P>
<P>
	There were eight two-gymnast teams, three men's artistic teams,  
three women's artistic teams and two women's rhythmic teams. Each 
team member performed in two events. 
</P>
<P>
	The runaway crowd favorite was 1996 Olympian Macready. Wearing  
sunglasses and a shimmering silver suit, Macready began his first 
routine robot-like, synchronizing his movements to a suitably 
mechanical soundtrack, then swinging onto the horizontal bars as 
Guns N' Roses' ``Welcome to the Jungle'' blared through Wells Fargo 
Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second round, Macready came out as a maestro, complete  
with tux and baton, and hamming his way through a routine to the 
``William Tell Overture.'' Macready had five 10s and a nine from 
the six judges. 
</P>
<P>
	The only performance to earn a 10 from all six judges was by  
rhythmic gymnast Mila Marinova with a ribbon. But it wasn't enough 
to overcome the overall performance of the team of Davis and 
Lacuesta, who between them have won the last four national 
championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good showcase for rhythmic because we're supposed to  
perform, we're supposed to express. It's great to have the audience 
there,'' Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	The performances were more show biz than athletic competition,  
and so was the judging. The judges included actresses Joan Van Ark 
(``Dallas and Knot's Landing''), Sean Young (``Blade Runner'' and 
``Ace Ventura, Pet Detective''), television actors James Avery 
(``Fresh Prince of Bel Air'') and Jimmy James (`NewsRadio''), 
recording artist Mya and ex-Dallas Cowboys quarterback Danny White. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
