<DOCNO> APW19990116.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:09:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How Vikings and Falcons Match Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Matchups for Sunday's NFC title game between 	
the Minnesota Vikings and Atlanta Falcons: 
</P>
<P>
                    *WHEN THE VIKINGS HAVE THE BALL 	
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings set an NFL record with 556 points in the regular  
season, never scored fewer than 24, went over 30 in 11 games, over 
40 four times and hit 50 once. And they're versatile. If Randall 
Cunningham (7), Cris Carter (80) and Randy Moss (84) are 
controlled, there's tight end Andrew Glover (82), running backs 
Robert Smith (26) and Leroy Hoard (44), and return man and 
third-down specialist David Palmer (22). In last Sunday's game 
against Arizona, Palmer even played a little quarterback, running 
and trying to pass from the shotgun. 
</P>
<P>
	But while teams know what's coming from Cunningham and his  
receivers, they can't do much to stop them. The Falcons may try to 
line up their best cornerback, Ray Buchanan (34) on Moss, but 
Buchanan is just 5-foot-9, giving Moss an 8-inch advantage. The 
other corner, Ronnie Bradford (23), is 5-10, so look for 6-2 nickel 
back Michael Booker (20) to see a lot of Moss. 
</P>
<P>
	Double-teaming Moss and Carter just gives Glover and Matthew  
Hatchette (89) more room -- Hatchette has assumed a bigger role 
since Jake Reed (86) was injured. Free safety Eugene Robinson (41) 
is the leader of the secondary and played the Vikings (without 
Moss) four times in two seasons in Green Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	The best way to top the passing game is to put pressure on  
Cunningham. The Falcons' Chuck Smith (90) is one of the league's 
unsung pass rushers, Lester Archambeau (92) led the team with 10 
sacks, and Travis Hall (98) and Shane Dronett (75) are effective 
inside. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Vikings' offensive line is one of the league's best.  
Left tackle Todd Steussie (73), left guard Randall McDaniel (64) 
and center Jeff Christy (62) are all going to the Pro Bowl and 
David Dixon (71) and Korey Stringer (77) weigh nearly 700 pounds 
together. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota had more trouble this season with big lines, and  
Atlanta's is relatively small. Hall weighs 300 pounds and Dronett 
has bulked up 25 pounds to 295, but Smith and Archambeau are 265 
and 275. 
</P>
<P>
	That could mean a lot of yards rushing for quick slasher Robert 	
Smith and Hoard, the short-yardage man. Smith had 1,187 yards 
during the season and Hoard averaged 4.2 yards a carry, a lot for a 
big back. But the Atlanta linebackers, Jessie Tuggle (58), 
Cornelius Bennett (97) and Henri Crockett (91), all had good years, 
particularly Bennett, who at 33 was thought to be past his prime. 
Tuggle is the NFL's leading active tackler, with 1,682 over a 
12-year career.	
</P>
<P>
                    *WHEN THE FALCONS HAVE THE BALL 	
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons' offense may be its best defense, if it can control  
the ball and clock by running Jamal Anderson (32), whose 1,846 
yards were the ninth most by any back in an NFL season. His 410 
regular-season carries set an NFL record. Anderson did it despite 
an offensive line that had to adjust from the run-and-shoot at the 
beginning of the 1997 season, meaning it had to learn run-blocking 
all over again. He also will be missing injured fullback Bob 
Christian, but Brian Koslowski (85), a journeyman tight end, has 
filled in well. The Falcons led the league in time of possession, 
more than 33 minutes a game, and they'll need to do that Sunday 
against a defense that can be exploited. 
</P>
<P>
	Left tackle Bob Whitfield (70), the only first-round pick on the  
offensive line, will probably play against perennial All-Pro John 
Randle if Randle starts at right end instead of at tackle, as 
expected. But the key run-stopper is nose tackle Jerry Ball (96), a 
338-pound, 12-year veteran who had his best season since his Pro 
Bowl days in Detroit nearly a decade ago. The Minnesota linebackers 
are relatively small but very quick, particularly Ed McDaniel (58), 
Dwayne Rudd (57) and Dixon Edwards (59). 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Chandler (12) had his best season for the Falcons with a  
quarterback rating of 100.9 that was fourth in the league, ahead of 
John Elway, Brett Favre and Troy Aikman among others. His two 
principal targets, Tony Martin (80) and Terance Mathis (81) both 
had over 1,100 yards receiving and 130 catches between them. Each 
averaged 17.9 yards a catch, making them deep threats against a 
Minnesota secondary that makes big plays but also gambles a lot. 
Right cornerback Jimmy Hitchcock (37) had seven interceptions, 
returning three for TDs and strong safety Robert Griffith (24) had 
five and is better than most strong safeties at man-to-man 
coverage. He often plays cornerback in nickel packages. 
</P>
<P>
	If both are double-covered look for tight end O.J. Santiago 	
(88).	
</P>
<P>
                           *SPECIAL TEAMS 	
</P>
<P>
	The kickers, Minnesota's Gary Anderson (1) and Atlanta's Morten  
Andersen (5), are 1-2 in career field goals (Anderson has 418 and 
Andersen 401). Neither has slowed down with age -- Anderson is 39, 
Andersen 38. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson had a perfect season -- 59-of-59 on extra points and  
35-of-35 on field goals. Andersen was almost as good, missing one 
extra point and going 23-of-28 on field goals. 
</P>
<P>
	But Minnesota has an extra weapon in punter Mitch Berger, who  
also handles kickoffs and had 42 touchbacks during the regular 
season. That's important. Of those kickoffs that were returned, 
four went for touchdowns and the special teams also gave up a punt 
return for a TD. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta's Tim Dwight (83) a potential problem for the Vikings.  
</P>
<P>
	Dwight averaged 27 yards a return for the Falcons and returned  
one for a touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer handles the kickoff and punt return duties for Minnesota. 	
He averaged four yards fewer than Dwight on kickoffs but had an 
88-yard TD return.	
</P>
<P>
                      *COACHING AND INTANGIBLES 	
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta's Dan Reeves, who underwent quadruple heart bypass  
surgery a month ago, has been in eight Super Bowls as player, 
assistant coach and head coach, losing in 1987, 1988 and 1990 as 
head coach of the Broncos. He has two former head coaches on his 
staff: defensive coordinator Rich Brooks, who coached the Rams in 
1995-96; and offensive line coach Art Shell, a Hall of Fame tackle 
as a player, who was coach of the Raiders for almost five seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	There's little postseason experience among the Falcons.  
</P>
<P>
	Chandler is in the playoffs for the first time in his 11-year  
career after playing for teams like Arizona, Indianapolis and Tampa 
Bay. Bennett played in four consecutive losing Super Bowls with 
Buffalo, and Robinson was in the last two with Green Bay. Martin 
(San Diego, 1995) and backup defensive back Randy Fuller 
(Pittsburgh, 1996) also have Super Bowl experience. White (Detroit, 
1992) and Buchanan (Indianapolis, 1996) have both played in 
conference championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota coach Dennis Green now has the longest tenure with one  
team, after Marty Schottenheimer quit in Kansas City. Green has 
been to the playoffs in six of his seven seasons, but his record is 
just 2-4. The victories came last Sunday against Arizona and last 
season against the Giants, when the Vikings rallied from a 
nine-point deficit in the final two minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Cunningham, who quarterbacked a star-studded but underachieving  
team in Philadelphia, has never gone this far in the playoffs. He's 
never been past the second round. The most experienced of the 
Vikings is Edwards, who played on three Super Bowl winners in 
Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest intangible in this game will be the noise.  
</P>
<P>
	While visitors have won four of the last 10 NFC title games,  
none has played indoors, where both artificial noise and the crowd 
often make it impossible for opposing offenses to hear signals. In 
Minnesota's 28-14 victory over Green Bay during the regular season, 
the Packers were called for five illegal procedure penalties on one 
touchdown drive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Apartments Have Risen on Quake Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The deathtrap that was Northridge Meadows has  
given way to a new apartment complex called Parc Ridge. There's a 
pool, a gym and a playground, and a sign that boasts ``Luxury 
Living.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago, Northridge Meadows had a sign, too. It promised  
``Luxury Resort Living.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sixteen people died there when the magnitude-6.7 Northridge  
earthquake struck at 4:31 a.m., Jan. 17, 1994. All lived on the 
first floor, crushed when the second and third stories collapsed 
onto them. 
</P>
<P>
	The Northridge quake was America's costliest natural disaster:  
72 dead; 9,000 injured and $25 billion in property damage. The 
Federal Emergency Management Agency provided $6.3 billion in 
assistance, but says nearly a third of those who applied for 
federal aid have yet to completely rebuild. 
</P>
<P>
	Parc Ridge, a 158-unit, three-story complex on Reseda Boulevard,  
opened in November with much fanfare from local politicians. The 
$16.8 million project was financed with city and federal housing 
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	There is nothing that betrays the death and destruction visited  
here five years ago. Some tenants didn't even know its predecessor 
was Northridge Meadows. 
</P>
<P>
	But most do know its past. Some, according to maintenance  
supervisor Lee Rosenberg, had priests bless their units before they 
moved in. Others, he said with uplifted eyebrows, moved in because 
of what happened here. 
</P>
<P>
	Along the driveway stand 16 trees, planted in honor of the dead.  
But there is nothing -- not a sign or a plaque -- that explains their 
significance. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't publicize or play it up out of respect for them,''  
said Eddie Cohen, whose Northridge Redevelopment Group owns the new 
complex. 
</P>
<P>
	``Them'' included Sharon and Phil Englar, who lived in No. 102  
and died holding hands, lying in bed. Darla Enos died in No. 123, 
crushed in her bedroom while her husband was already up and 
drinking coffee in the kitchen; he survived. 
</P>
<P>
	The old 164-unit Northridge Meadows was doomed by its location  
near the quake's epicenter and by outdated building codes. Its 
walls tore like cardboard. 
</P>
<P>
	Structural requirements enacted since the quake require thicker  
concrete walls, and additional connections between framing and 
foundations to prevent buildings from sliding. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel really good about what we did here,'' Cohen said. ``We  
provided the community with a high standard and incredible 
amenities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parc Ridge has rented 95 units, Cohen said. Some are set aside  
for low-income renters with a two-bedroom apartment going for $625, 
compared to market value of $1,095 per month. 
</P>
<P>
	Not a single Northridge Meadows tenant moved back, but some of  
them can't forget. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people who used to live here come by and look at  
it,'' Cohen said. ``They talk about how scary it was and about how 
safe this looks now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most renters said they are relatively untroubled by the site's  
past. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to go on,'' said 22-year-old college student Arny  
Pollack, who lives on the first floor. ``Everything here is up to 
code now. I do feel bad about the people who died here. But people 
die. It's a way of life. And you've got to live life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Upstairs and down the hall, Raja Hamawe, 32, said she knows what  
happened five years ago. ``I think about it and it makes me 
scared,'' said the mother of two. ``But it is such a nice building 
now. It is safe now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others are concerned not about structural safety but about  
displaced spirits. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty scary,'' said Luciano Bayardo, 22, who lives with  
Marlene Estrada, 18, and their 14-month-old daughter, Clarissa. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think about it at night,'' Bayardo said. ``I know it sounds  
weird, but one night I went to bed and locked the doors and turned 
out the lights and the next morning I came out and all the doors 
were unlocked and the lights were on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody who comes here, all our family, they say watch out  
for ghosts and stuff,'' she said with a chuckle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
