<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 15:12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bauer Wins Cross-Country Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RUMFORD, Maine (AP) -- John Bauer, who's always skied well in the  
national cross-country championships, earned his ninth U.S. title 
Saturday in the men's 30-kilometer race while three-time Olympian 
Nina Kemppel of Anchorage, Alaska, added her fourth women's crown. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer, a two-time Olympian from Champlin, Minn., covered the  
four-lap course in 1 hour, 13 minutes, 43.4 seconds, 8.3 seconds 
ahead of 
</P>
<P>
	Carl Swenson of Boulder, Colo., a professional mountain bike  
racer and former Dartmouth College ski captain who raced in the '94 
Olympics. Marcus Nash of Fryeburg, Maine, another two-time Olympic 
racer, was third in 1:14.37.5. 
</P>
<P>
	Kemppel, who already has qualified for the world championships  
next month in Austria, was timed in 43:43.4 over the two 7.5K laps 
at Black Mountain. 
</P>
<P>
	Jen Douglas, a former Middlebury College racer from Ketchum,  
Idaho, took the silver medal in 44:07.5 and University of Vermont 
skier Tessa Benoit of South Pomfret, Vt., was third in 45:08.9. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a struggle for me out there today,'' Kemppel said. ``I  
was cramping up really bad from about 9 Ks. It was a struggle just 
to get up the hills, definitely not ideal conditions for me ... six 
inches of mushy snow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the men raced at mid-morning, snow conditions were ``rocket  
fast,'' Bauer said. ``I was wearing glasses but I had to keep 
blinking away tears in my eyes because of the speed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He hopes to upset recent history, he said, when he would ski  
well in the national championships and then run into sickness and 
other problems overseas. ``I've been healthy all along so far, and 
I'm going to stay healthy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm feeling too consistent this year to have anything go  
wrong,'' he said. ``I didn't feel I had a great race today, like I 
was pushing myself. I was tired but I don't hurt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Five men and four women will be chosen from these races to join  
Kemppel in Ramsau, Austria, Feb. 18-28 for the Nordic World 
Championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
