<DOCNO> APW19990116.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 01:52:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Power Outage Disrupts Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A power outage at the Federal Aviation  
Administration's regional air traffic control center disrupted air 
travel throughout the Northwest and delayed flights for about 8,000 
passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	The outage and the failure of a backup generator lasted about 35  
minutes Friday when controllers lost radar and radio 
communications. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA halted all plane departures in the region until the  
problem was fixed, which delayed more than 8,000 passengers, some 
for several hours. No safety problems were reported, officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has a domino effect,'' said Sue Warner-Bean, a Horizon  
Airlines spokeswoman. ``If a flight is delayed on one route, then 
the next flight and the next flight and the next flight is 
delayed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle-bound jets were left waiting at distant airports, and 46  
planes were temporarily grounded at Seattle-Tacoma International 
Airport, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem began about 2 p.m. Friday at the Seattle Air Route  
Traffic Control Center, which controls air traffic for all of 
Washington, the western two-thirds of Oregon, the Idaho panhandle, 
small portions of Montana and Nevada and a portion of northern 
California. It is one of 20 such centers nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``The backup power supply generator didn't work when it was  
supposed to,'' said Mitch Barker, FAA spokesman. ``We don't know 
what triggered that having to come on. It may have been a 
commercial power blip.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for Puget Sound Energy, which supplies power to  
the FAA facility, said electricity to the building was not cut off 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	During Friday's outage, controllers used backup communications  
at Sea-Tac Airport to communicate with pilots in the air, Barker 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
