<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fox Entertainment Chief Wants More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- Fox's new entertainment chief wants the  
television network to be about more than cartoons and car crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	Doug Herzog, who replaced Peter Roth last week as head of  
programming at Fox, indicated the network may be overdoing it with 
edgy reality shows. His top priority is to develop comedy programs 
that use real actors instead of animated characters, he said 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox has struck ratings gold with reality shows that depict  
animals attacking, buildings collapsing and cars crashing. Herzog 
told television critics at a news conference that the specials will 
still have a place on Fox, just not such a prominent one. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't want to rely on the stuff long-term,'' said the  
former Comedy Central president. ``It's great for short-term gains. 
We need to look at it like that. You could probably say that we've 
been doing a little too much of that lately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fox is also being overrun this year with prime-time animated  
characters. In addition to ``The Simpsons'' and ``King of the 
Hill,'' it recently debuted ``The PJ's,'' created by Eddie Murphy. 
Two more cartoons will debut in March: ``Family Guy'' and 
``Futurama,'' the latter created by ``Simpsons'' creator Matt 
Groening. Except for ``That '70s Show'' and ``Ally McBeal,'' live 
comedies are absent from Fox. 
</P>
<P>
	Herzog said cartoons are easier to make distinctive and can  
often be cheaper to produce than shows with live actors -- no small 
consideration in the financially constricted world of network 
television. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best thing about animated characters is they can't get  
bored or tired and run off to make a movie,'' Herzog said. 
</P>
<P>
	But there are limits. Herzog, whose success at Comedy Central  
was largely due to ``South Park,'' said those foul-mouthed cartoon 
characters weren't right for broadcast television. 
</P>
<P>
	Comedies with live actors ``are in desperate need of  
reinvention,'' he said. ``Whether I can figure it out will tell the 
tale of whether I can make this job or not.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
