<HEADLINE> Jewel Thief on Run Dies As Pauper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A convicted jewel thief who lived the high life for  
years while on the run from police died as a pauper. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward Henry Cook was believed responsible for at least $17  
million in jewelry heists. At various times, he sported a 28-carat 
diamond, drove Cadillacs and lived in an elegant villa in the 1960s 
and 1970s, even though he had no visible means of support. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities relied on fingerprints to determine that he was the  
emaciated 73-year-old man who checked into a $49-a-night motel in 
Pompano Beach in Nov. 15 under a false name and died a few days 
later, the FBI said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	He died of heart and renal failure, officials said.  
</P>
<P>
	Cook was dubbed a ``a master criminal'' by Miami detectives  
after a $1.7 million robbery of a Pompano Beach jeweler in 1963. He 
was given life in prison, but the sentence was overturned on a 
technicality and he was not retried. 
</P>
<P>
	He had been on the run since 1989, when he was indicted in  
connection with a $2 million burglary of a Port Arthur, Texas, 
jewelry store four years earlier. The loot was never recovered, 
said FBI spokesman Mike Fabregas. 
</P>
<P>
	Cook's group was accused of taking $14 million in merchandise in  
two years from eight jewelry store burglaries across the South, 
including Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, Cook was featured on the TV show America's Most Wanted  
as a thief who stayed in the best hotels and always one step ahead 
of police. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said Cook's gangs typically cut neatly through  
ceilings and walls, bypassed sophisticated alarm systems, and used 
acetylene torches to slice into safes. Often they resealed the 
building so the crime would not immediately be discovered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rey-Bellet Wins Downhill, Super-G </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. ANTON, Austria (AP) -- Corinne Rey-Bellet of Switzerland, who  
had never before won a race, made World Cup history Saturday by 
winning two on the same day. 
</P>
<P>
	By capturing a downhill and a super-giant slalom within four  
hours, Rey-Bellet became the first skier in World Cup history to 
win two different events in one day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything I did today was just great,'' Rey-Bellet said.  
</P>
<P>
	``The piste was perfect. I was dreaming of a World Cup victory,  
but I never thought I would win two in one day,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ski officials first said that Rey-Bellet had equaled the feat  
achieved by Erika Hess of Switzerland at Alpe d'Huez, France, in 
1982. 
</P>
<P>
	After checking their records again, however, they discovered  
that Hess had indeed won a slalom and the first heat of a giant 
slalom on the same day. But the second heat of the giant slalom was 
run the next day, meaning Rey-Bellet was indeed the first to 
accomplish the feat. 
</P>
<P>
	Rey-Bellet stormed down the icy, bumpy Kandahar course in one  
minute, 28.01 seconds to win the downhill, then mastered the same, 
but shortened course in the Super-G race, clocking 1:23.18. 
</P>
<P>
	World Cup leader Alexandra Meissnitzer of Austria had a  
frustrating day, finishing sixth in the downhill and second in the 
Super-G. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Meissnitzer padded her World Cup overall lead and now has  
1,100 points. Hilde Gerg of Germany, third in the downhill and 12th 
in the Super-G, remained second with 782. 
</P>
<P>
	Michaela Dorfmeister of Austria finished second in the downhill,  
covering the 2,377-meters in 1:28.20 
</P>
<P>
	She capped a fine showing by finishing third in the Super-G,  
clocking 1:23.59 on the 2,127-meter course that had become softer 
throughout the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Rey-Bellet missed the entire 1997 World Cup season after tearing  
knee ligaments. She then hired a psychologist to help her regain 
self-confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a super run. It's a great feeling to finally win a World  
Cup race. That's what I trained for all these years,'' Rey-Bellet 
said after her downhill victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Rey-Bellet's previous best was a third place in a giant slalom  
in Crans-Montana, Switzerland, in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	But she was fourth in the last downhill in Veysonnaz,  
Switzerland, last month, and clocked the fastest times in both 
training runs Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been around for quite some time and I've been gathering  
experience'' the Swiss said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The training times gave me confidence for the race,'' she  
said. ``I felt good yesterday, I felt I was steady.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The course was harder today but I skied better than yesterday.  
I skied the bottom part perfectly,'' said Rey-Bellet, who gave 
Switzerland its first downhill victory in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Originally scheduled for Friday, the downhill had to be moved to  
Saturday after a heavy snowfall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
