<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kjus Extends Downhill Standings Lead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WENGEN, Switzerland (AP) -- Norwegian Lasse Kjus strengthened his  
lead in the World Cup downhill standings by capturing his third 
victory of season in the discipline Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus, who missed the last World Cup meet because of recurring  
bronchitis, covered the circuit's longest and most demanding 
Lauberhorn course in 2 minutes, 25.10 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	He finished the 2.7 miles more than half a second ahead of  
Olympic bronze medallist Hannes Trinkl, whose second-place finish 
started a run of five consecutive Austrian skiers. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinkl had his best showing in five years, clocking 2:25.66,  
just .01 ahead of teammate Hans Knauss. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone has to stop the Austrians,'' joked Kjus, the 1996  
overall World Cup champion. ``But seriously, I am just happy I won 
even though I was not 100 percent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus, who won the season-opening downhill in Val d'Isere,  
France, also placed first and second in a double downhill in Val 
Gardena, Italy, just before Christmas. 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus' bronchitis prevented him from racing the last downhill in  
Bormio, Italy, won by Hermann Maier. Kjus was also forced to miss a 
giant slalom in Adelboden, Switzerland, earlier in the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus leads the downhill with 380 points, 110 ahead of Maier, the  
reigning World Cup overall, super-G and giant slalom champion, who 
has made the downhill title a goal this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a hungry man,'' Kjus said of Maier. ``He wants to win  
everything but I will make it tough on him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While his fourth-place finish Saturday earned him another 40  
points, Maier was was unhappy with his time of 2:25.75. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very disappointed,'' said Maier, the winner of a shortened  
downhill moved to Wengen from Veysonnaz last year. ``If one of the 
coaches could have told me how far behind I was a third of the way 
down, I would have given up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 26-year-old Austrian added to his lead atop the overall  
standings where he has 961 points, 242 ahead of his nearest 
challenger Kjetil Andre Aamodt of Norway, who finished seventh on 
Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
