<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Countries Seek Stable Exchange Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Finance ministers from leading  
European and Asian economies Saturday agreed on tighter cooperation 
to stabilize exchange rates and avoid the sort of market chaos that 
is rocking Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	The 25 ministers wrapped up two days of talks with calls for  
action to prevent exchange rate jolts, but they said they were 
waiting for further talks with the United States before tackling 
any specifics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone agrees we need to take steps to avoid swings in  
exchange rates,'' said German Finance Minister Oskar Lafontaine, 
who chaired the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Lafontaine said the crisis in Brazil and earlier tumult in Asian  
and Russian markets showed that ``leaving everything wide open 
gives rise to difficulties. ... It's our duty to get to grips with 
this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The same topics -- Brazil and action on currency -- were expected  
to dominate the agenda later Saturday in Frankfurt when deputy 
finance ministers from the G-7 group of world economic powers meet, 
including U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Europe-Asia meeting, Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi  
Miyazawa said concrete proposals would need to be worked out later 
in talks involving the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Ministers shied away from controversial proposals from Germany  
and Japan that would coordinate buying and selling by central banks 
to keep currencies within fixed bands or target values and thereby 
soften exchange rate shocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian Treasury Minister Carlo Ciampi said it was too early to  
talk about such plans, while Lafontaine said target rates for 
leading world currencies could only come when the U.S., European 
and Japanese economies were on the same track. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first step is for economies to converge. Economic policy  
decisions need to be coordinated,'' Lafontaine told a news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	He warned there was a ``need to scale down growth expectations  
worldwide'' following the turbulence in Latin America, Asia and 
Russia. But European and Asian officials sought to downplay the 
potential impact of Brazil's woes on their markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Michel Camdessus, managing director of the International  
Monetary Fund, was prevented from attending by snow in Washington, 
but in a written statement, he predicted Asia's ``recovery will be 
underway by the end of 1999.'' 
</P>
<P>
	European Union Finance Commissioner Yves-Thibault de Silguy said  
``growth in Europe will be more robust than in other parts of the 
world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miyazawa floated the idea of anchoring Asian currencies to a  
basket comprising the Japanese yen, U.S. dollar and the new 
European currency, the euro, rather than leaving them pegged to the 
dollar. He said the launch of the euro as the common currency of 11 
EU nations on Jan. 1 was a good opportunity to look afresh at the 
world financial system. 
</P>
<P>
	Elaborating on the ``flexible stability'' concept put forward by  
Lafontaine, officials said it would involve closer monitoring of 
capital movements and greater coordinated intervention by central 
banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Ministers agreed a closer eye needed to be kept on speculators,  
whose sudden movements of huge amounts of foreign currencies have 
been blamed for undermining markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to start with (controlling) short-term flows of  
capital, speculation,'' Lafontaine said. ``Surveillance should be 
stepped up, that was universally agreed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Britain's Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown called for  
the creation of a global financial watchdog to closely monitor 
potential crisis spots and become ``the world's early warning 
system for regional and global economic risk.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
