<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO To Hold Emergency Kosovo Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO will hold an emergency session Sunday in  
Brussels to consider a response to the execution-style massacre of 
dozens of people in southern Kosovo, the State Department spokesman 
said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright proposed the meeting.  
</P>
<P>
	Her spokesman, James P. Rubin, said the ambassadors to the 16  
North Atlantic Treaty Organization countries would convene at NATO 
headquarters in Brussels ``in light of this outrageous situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin pointed out that NATO in October developed contingency  
plans for dealing with Kosovo, the Serbian province where ethnic 
Albanian separatists have been fighting with Serb police and 
troops. 
</P>
<P>
	``There should be no doubt of NATO's resolve,'' Rubin said.  
</P>
<P>
	NATO's contingency plans involve the possible bombing of Serb  
installations. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, the U.S. official said a U.S.-brokered cease-fire in  
Kosovo was shaky. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton condemned the atrocity ``in the strongest  
possible terms'' and called the atrocity ``a clear violation'' of 
the Serbs' ceasefire agreement with NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a deliberate and indiscriminate act of murder  
designed to sow fear among the people of Kosovo,'' Clinton said 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	National security advisers conferred on Saturday at the White  
House, and Rubin said Albright spoke by telephone with several NATO 
counterparts, including foreign ministers in Great Britain, France, 
Germany and Norway. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright discussed strategy for a NATO meeting she hoped could  
be scheduled Sunday or Monday, Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	National Security Council spokesman David Leavy said discussions  
with U.S. allies would occur ``on a number of different levels to 
address this and move forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of bodies were scattered around the village of Racak on  
Saturday, a day after a fierce attack by Serb forces on ethnic 
Albanian villages. The death toll, which included elderly men, 
apparently is the highest in a single attack since the Oct. 12 
cease-fire agreement brokered by U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents of Racak village said Serb forces rounded up the  
victims, drove them up a hill and shot them. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been problems and violations of the agreement for  
many weeks now, and clearly it is shaky,'' Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not as bad as it was last fall, but it's heading rapidly  
in 
</P>
<P>
	hat direction,'' Rubin said. ``If there are reprisals or a  
spiral of escalation as a result of this atrocity, we could be 
there very soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a harshly worded statement Saturday, Clinton, who was briefed  
by National Security Adviser Sandy Berger, said Serb authorities 
must immediately identify the perpetrators. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a clear violation of the commitments Serbian authorities  
have made to NATO. There can be no justification for it,'' Clinton 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Serbs also ``must withdraw security forces, carry out all  
the commitments they have made to NATO and cease their 
repression,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
