<DOCNO> APW19990116.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saturday's Impeachment Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	--House prosecutors wrapped up their three-day opening  
presentation with Rep. Henry Hyde telling senators the presidency 
could be ``permanently damaged'' if President Clinton is not 
convicted and removed from office. 
</P>
<P>
	--Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott asked Democrats for a meeting  
to discuss ``safeguards'' and to ``resolve in advance any 
complications'' in case witnesses are called at the trial. Senate 
Democratic Leader Tom Daschle rejected the request, saying ``it is 
my hope that such arrangements will ultimately prove unnecessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--The president delivered a radio address from the Oval Office  
calling on Americans to engage in community service in honor Martin 
Luther King Jr. Day. He then settled down with aides to rehearse 
his State of the Union speech. 
</P>
<P>
	--Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., made a folksy presentation  
designed to put a human face on a case dominated by legal 
distinctions. He told senators in his closing argument that a high 
crime occurs simply ``if a high person hurts a person of low 
means'' and that Clinton did that when he tried to ``fix'' the 
Paula Jones case. 
</P>
<P>
	--Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., reminded senators they have  
impeached and removed federal judges for perjury. ``The Senate 
should not establish a lower standard of integrity for the 
president,'' he argued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
