<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Edwin Moses at Drug Testing Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- The IOC and other governing bodies in  
sports, to gain credibility with athletes, must demonstrate they 
want to be fair and impartial in drug testing, hurdles great Edwin 
Moses said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the critical function they will have to do is  
establish that they are serious about the problems and maintain 
focus on major issues,'' Moses said at a forum organized by Duke to 
examine issues raised by the testing of athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	Moses was joined by former Olympic swimmer Donna de Varona, USA  
Track &AMP; Field executive Craig Masback as well as doctors and 
professors at the meeting, which hopes to influence an IOC drug 
conference scheduled to take place next month in Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Moses said sports governing bodies must be aware of athletes'  
rights and due process. And in today's fast-paced society, just 
finding athletes to test them is difficult, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're looking for athletes all over the world, it's hard  
keeping a moving roster of people,'' he said during a break in the 
task force meeting of the Duke Conference on Drugs in Sport. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC is worried that the issue is tarnishing the image o its  
games, especially in light of the bribery scandal involving Salt 
Lake City's bid for the next Winter Games, said John Weistart, 
co-director of the Duke law school's new Sports Law and Policy 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless they control it, it poses a similar threat to  
commercial sponsorship,'' Weistart said. 
</P>
<P>
	Doriane Lambelet Coleman, a forum organizer who competed  
internationally in track and field in the 1980s, said Saturday's 
meeting also will be used to jump-start a larger drug conference in 
May. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's forum -- the first project for the new policy center --  
is important because of the cross-section of participants, said 
Coleman, also a Duke law lecturer. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are all at one table for the first time to try to talk  
about developing a model to resolve issues of drugs and sports with 
a particular emphasis on the Olympic sports,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Presenting an aboveboard testing program to young people is also  
important, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Olympic sports sort of grows with children as a target,''  
Coleman said. ``There's been people here who said it's important we 
present definitively and with integrity why (doping is) a problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
