<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jarrett Wins 60-Meter Dash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ja'Warren Hooker, make way for Patrick Jarrett.  
</P>
<P>
	Hooker, the 1998 NCAA indoor 55-meter champion and the  
third-place finisher in the 100 meters at the NCAA outdoor 
championships, was upset by the unheralded Jarrett in the 60-meter 
dash Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The stunning victory by the 25-year-old New York Tech runner  
over the Washington sophomore came at the inaugural New York Sports 
Museum Collegiate Invitational at the Armory Track and Field 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett, the New York state 100 and 200 champion in 1990 and  
1991, first beat the injured Hooker in the trial heats in 6.77 
seconds to 6.89, then came back 30 minutes later and won the final 
in 6.73. 
</P>
<P>
	Hooker, competing with his left foot heavily taped because of  
shin splints, finished second in 6.77. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Jarrett won the 200 in a sparkling 21.21, faster than his  
outdoor best by .01 seconds. The ailing Hooker finished fourth in 
the 200 in 21.82. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett was surprised that he beat a sprinter like Hooker,  
considered one of the best in college. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't know who he was until they announced him before the  
heats,'' said Jarrett, a member of New York Tech's winning 
400-meter relay team at the NCAA Division II Championships and a 
member of the Jamaican 400 relay team that finished fourth at last 
summer's Goodwill Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``There might have been a problem if I knew who he was.''  
</P>
<P>
	Hooker was the one with the problem Saturday night.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not blaming the injury,'' Hooker said, before heading  
toward the first aid room for treatment. ``I didn't run a great 
race. I'll be back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He apparently injured the shin while overtraining in Seattle.  
</P>
<P>
	While Hooker was not at his best, Jarrett was superb, especially  
for someone who claims he ``hates indoors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He took the lead from the outset and held off the hard-charging  
but laboring Hooker. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a big accomplishment for me,'' Jarrett said. ``There  
was no pressure thinking about him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm so confident in my training now. If I run my race, I'm  
going to compete with the best. And if I run my race, I'm going to 
win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He showed his 60 victory was no fluke by easily winning the 200,  
beating Ohio State's Andrew Pierce by .30 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hold me down!'' Jarrett shouted after his 200 triumph. ``I'm  
going to take off. I'm a well-oiled machine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Jarrett's performances were the scene stealers, there were  
some other outstanding efforts in the 10-team competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Pierce won the 400 in 46.85, breaking the Armory record, and  
anchored Ohio State to victory in the 1,600 relay with a 400 leg of 
45.6. The Buckeyes were timed in 3;10.29. 
</P>
<P>
	Villanova's Carmen Douma, the NCAA indoor mile champion and the  
NCAA outdoor 1,500-meter champion, ran away from the field in the 
women's field, winning by about 50 meters in 4:51.69. 
</P>
<P>
	And Dominique Calloway, an NCAA finalist in last year's outdoor  
championships, led a 1-2 Ohio State finish in the women's 60-meter 
hurdles. Calloway was timed in 8.34, making her a provisional 
qualifier for this year's NCAA indoor championships. Donika 
Merriman was second at 8.40. 
</P>
<P>
	George Mason's Angie Brown, the NCAA long jump champion, won  
with a modest leap of 19 feet, 11 1-2 inches. 
</P>
<P>
	And Villanova's Carrie Tollefson, the NCAA 5,000-meter cross  
country champion, took the women's 3,000 in 9:33.74. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
