<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Countries Seek Stable Exchange Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- With Brazil providing a fresh example  
of the havoc drastic currency swings can cause, Europe's biggest 
economies and Japan pushed for international measures today to 
promote more stable exchange rates. 
</P>
<P>
	But the finance ministers meeting in Frankfurt failed to put  
forward any detailed plan to tame currency markets or smooth out 
capital flows. And the seemingly contradictory terms they used to 
state their goals -- ``flexible stability'' and ``free movement of 
capital, but ... controlled'' -- indicated how difficult it would be 
to achieve them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone agrees we need to take steps to avoid swings in  
exchange rates,'' German Finance Minister Oskar Lafontaine said at 
the end of the two-day meeting of European Union and Asian finance 
ministers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have discovered that leaving everything wide open gives  
rise to difficulties'' -- like this week's Brazil crisis, he said, 
refering to the plunge in the South American nation's stock market 
after the government devalued its currency. ``It's our duty to get 
to grips with this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But his Japanese counterpart, Kiichi Miyazawa, conceded their  
idea of an ``exchange rate regime among major currencies'' to 
reduce ``excessive volatility'' was still undefined -- and faces 
significant opposition from Washington and from central bankers 
like Wim Duisenberg, president of the new European Central Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is wary of any talk of exchange-rate ties,  
warning such plans could be hugely expensive and have a history of 
failure. 
</P>
<P>
	Participants at the Frankfurt meeting said they hoped  
differences could be worked out among the Group of Seven leading 
industrial countries, including the United States. Finance 
ministers from the group are to meet Feb. 20 in Bonn and a summit 
of leaders is set for June. 
</P>
<P>
	Miyazawa suggested emerging Asian economies link their  
currencies to the dollar, yen and Europe's new single currency, the 
euro, in a trade-weighted average known as a currency basket. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea would be somewhat of a throwback to the systems that  
prevailed in Asia up to when the financial crisis there began in 
mid-1997, only this time with less reliance on the dollar alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Miyazawa said a couple Asian ministers expressed interest in the  
idea, but others reacted skeptically. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Thailand went into a deep problem, we were pegged to the  
basket,'' Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda noted with a 
chuckle. 
</P>
<P>
	Thailand maintained a basket system that had kept its currency,  
the baht, artificially high and caused a massive sell down when it 
was abandoned under pressure in July 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany, Japan and France also called for controls on currency  
speculators, particularly the secretive investment companies known 
as hedge funds, which buy and sell huge amounts of foreign 
currencies and have been blamed for provoking market upheavals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is necessary to enhance financial sector supervision,''  
Lafontaine and Miyazawa said in a joint statement that called for 
tighter reporting requirements for hedge funds and financial 
institutions investing in them. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Europeans appeared to back away from earlier proposals  
for target rates, or bands within which the leading world 
currencies -- the dollar, yen and euro -- would be allowed to 
fluctuate. Central banks would have to coordinate buying and 
selling to prevent currencies lurching outside the bands. 
</P>
<P>
	``Target rates are not the only solution,'' said Italian  
Treasury Minister Carlo Ciampi. ``We are not talking about controls 
in the old sense of the term.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
