<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rey-Bellet Wins Women's Downhill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. ANTON, Austria (AP) -- Corinne Rey-Bellet of Switzerland  
stunned the downhill favorites to capture her first World Cup 
victory today. 
</P>
<P>
	The 26-year-old Rey-Bellet stormed down the icy, bumpy Kandahar  
course in 1 minute, 28.01 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Austrian Michaela Dorfmeister was second in 1:28.20, and Hilde  
Gerg of Germany third in 1:28.30. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a super run. It's a great feeling to finally win a World  
Cup race. That's what I trained for all these years,'' Rey-Bellet 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rey-Bellet's previous best finish was third in a giant slalom in  
Crans-Montana, Switzerland, in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	But she was fourth in the last downhill at Veysonnaz,  
Switzerland, in December, and clocked the fastest times in both 
training runs Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The training times gave me confidence for the race,'' she  
said. ``I felt good yesterday, I felt I was steady. 
</P>
<P>
	``The course was harder today but I skied better than yesterday.  
I skied the bottom part perfectly,'' said Rey-Bellet, who gave 
Switzerland its first downhill victory of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	World Cup leader Alexandra Meissnitzer of Austria finished  
sixth, .87 seconds behind Rey-Bellet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am disappointed of course,'' Meissnitzer said. ``I tried too  
hard. I should have skied more smoothly. I lost half a second just 
after the start.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Renate Goetschl of Austria, the World Cup downhill champion and  
two-time winner this season, was fourth, .68 seconds behind 
Rey-Bellet. 
</P>
<P>
	``During the race I didn't think I would achieve a good  
result,'' Dorfmeister said. ``The visibility was very bad on parts 
of the course and the preparation of the skies played a very 
important role.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gerg said she made ``a big mistake.''  
</P>
<P>
	``I drifted too close to the net. Later I made up some time but  
I couldn't catch up,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The downhill was followed by a Super-G. Originally scheduled for  
Friday, the downhill had to be moved to today after a heavy 
snowfall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
