<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rochon Takes World Cup Dual Moguls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STEAMBOAT SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) -- Canadian skiers Stephane Rochon  
and Pierre-Alexandre Rousseau finished 1-2 Saturday, dominating the 
first World Cup dual moguls event of the season while Sandra 
Schmitt of Germany picked up her first victory as she won the 
women's contest despite a steady snow. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm having a good time watching my teammate,'' Rochon said at  
the midpoint of the Sprint Shootout weekend ``because he's so 
excited, so happy and jumping around after making his first podium. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember my first top-3, two years ago in Breckenridge, and  
I was the same way. And today I have my first win in dual moguls 
and that makes me very excited, too,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Rochon said the day-long snow was deceptive because it created  
soft snow conditions on the course for a brief time ``but the other 
skiers would push it to the side, so it was not always so soft. You 
had to be careful and to keep your focus; it was a long day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the women's semifinals, Schmitt defeated local favorite Ann  
Battelle while Swedish skier Marja Elfman beat Brooke Ballachey of 
South Lake Tahoe, Calif. Schmitt then edged Elfman while Battelle 
earned her second top-3 of the season, beating Ballachey, her 
roommate this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great having a World Cup in your hometown,'' Battelle  
said, ``but it's also pretty stressful. I spent a lot of time 
skiing this week, maybe too much, but getting up on the mountain 
skiing was the only way, sometimes, to get away. 
</P>
<P>
	``Brooke'll find that out next week at Heavenly; I've been  
telling her it'll be hectic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The weekend winds up with aerials on Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
