<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Republican Lays Out Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's impeachment trial has not  
consumed all of Congress' attention, a top House Republican said 
today, citing GOP plans to improve schools, offer tax relief and 
preserve Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	In the weekly GOP radio address, Rep. Tillie Fowler of Florida  
laid out some of the priorities for House Republican members in the 
year ahead, starting with education. 
</P>
<P>
	Fowler, vice chairwoman of the House Republican Conference,  
outlined plans to ensure more money goes to classrooms and schools 
are more accessible to parents. 
</P>
<P>
	While Fowler said she expects Clinton to support a greater  
investment in education, she hoped the president would make sure 
the money ends up in local schools ``rather than in an expanded 
education bureaucracy in Washington, D.C.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fowler said she would like Clinton, in his State of the Union  
address Tuesday night, to offer a plan to rescue the troubled 
Social Security system -- a priority he outlined in his speech last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will join with you next week in listening to the president,  
and in hoping that along with promises about saving Social 
Security, he will also offer a plan to save it,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Providing tax relief for American families should be another  
objective for the year ahead, Fowler said, stressing that a budget 
surplus makes this feasible. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the president remembers that the surplus is not the  
government's money. It's your money. And you are entitled to 
getting some of it back,'' she told listeners. 
</P>
<P>
	To accomplish these goals, Congress has to leave behind ``the  
acrimony of last year'' and work together, Fowler said. 
</P>
<P>
	She resolved that in 1999 Republicans would ``focus our energies  
on results, not rhetoric; on similarities, not differences; and on 
action, not political posturing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
