<DOCNO> APW19990116.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jet Players Have Playoff Experience </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Here's how inexperienced in playoff situations the  
New York Jets really are: 19 of their players have been in the 
postseason, including 11 who have played in a Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Collectively, of course, the Jets aren't nearly as playoff savvy  
as the Denver Broncos, who won the NFL title last year and are in 
the Super Bowl chase for the third straight year. New York's last 
postseason appearance was in 1991, a short-lived one-game affair, 
and it hasn't been to the AFC Championship game since 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the Jets aren't exactly novices when it comes to the kind  
of pressure that accompanies Sunday's game for the AFC crown. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have enough maturity on this team,'' said Bill Parcells, who  
coached the Giants to two Super Bowl victories -- one over Denver -- 
and lost with New England in the big game before overseeing the 
Jets' stunning turnaround from 1-15 to the verge of their first 
Super Bowl in 30 years. ``It is not like a team without playoff 
experience. We have quite a few who do have it for various teams 
and situations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we are inexperienced. If we were, it would have  
showed up last week. But Denver certainly has an edge there in 
these games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York actually played more pressurized games this season than  
Denver. The Broncos, seeking a sixth Super Bowl appearance, surged 
to a 13-0 start, pursuing an historic unbeaten season. 
</P>
<P>
	But is that the same as playing each week with playoff or  
division race survival on the line? The Jets needed road wins in 
New England, Kansas City, Tennessee, Miami and Buffalo during their 
12-4 regular season to reach the top of the AFC East. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gave us a lot of confidence to go into places like Miami  
and Buffalo and win on the road with so much at stake,'' said 
quarterback Vinny Testaverde, the AFC's leading passer, just ahead 
of Denver star John Elway. ``We know we can win on the road. But we 
also know this is a tough game. We feel like we can get it done if 
we play good football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Good football might not be enough at Mile High Stadium, where  
the Broncos have won 18 straight games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets need to be stingy right away to avoid Denver  
duplicating its trademark quick start. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only did the Broncos lead the AFC in scoring with 501 points  
(the Jets scored 416), they outscored opponents 144-54 in the first 
quarter and 156-87 in the second. By halftime, the Broncos were in 
control nearly every week, leading each home game but one -- they 
were 21-21 with Kansas City -- and averaging a 23-8 edge. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that the Broncos are slouches in any portion of a game. But  
with NFL Most Valuable Player Terrell Davis spearheading the 
attack, they are dominant early. Often, that has rendered the final 
30 minutes of games insignificant. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Denver players say there's no way they'll have anything  
but a positive edge Sunday. No nerves or jitters, other than the 
eagerness to get after the opponent and get back to the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could say what we went through last year is an  
advantage,'' said safety Steve Atwater, referring to how the 
Broncos used the wild-card route to the championship. ``But we've 
got to do the things we did last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we have to want it even moreso than last year. I hope  
we have a feeling like we're underdogs and go out and make things 
happen, which was our attitude last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the Jets went 9-7 and barely missed qualifying for  
the playoffs. Parcells then brought in such key free agents at 
Testaverde, Curtis Martin, Keith Byars, Kevin Mawae and Anthony 
Pleasant. They have been among the leaders of the team's 
resurgence. 
</P>
<P>
	All of them, with their teammates, will carry the same fever and  
passion into Sunday's matchup that the Broncos bring. And nearly as 
much big-game experience. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
