<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calamity May Offer Opportunities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Disaster looms on several fronts in the  
Worldwatch Institute's millennial-ending look at the planet, but 
researchers see a possible economic boom for governments and 
companies that commit to head off social and environmental 
collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	Avoiding calamity ``represents the greatest investment  
opportunity in history,'' says institute founder Lester R. Brown, 
pointing to the spread of efforts to recycle raw materials in 
several industries and development of alternative energy sources, 
particularly wind power. 
</P>
<P>
	He cites one effort by a large U.S.-based corporation,  
Interface, to lease and recycle industrial carpet products now 
manufactured in seven countries and sold in 110. The company 
chairman agrees with Brown's concerns but says Interface's efforts 
to develop and lease totally recyclable products are short of 
spectacular in a $1.3 billion business. 
</P>
<P>
	``The marketplace is not really ready for it yet,'' said  
Interface head Ray Anderson of Atlanta, Ga., who has written a 
book, ``Mid-Course Correction,'' on the need to create industries 
that return ``every valuable molecule'' for possible use again. 
</P>
<P>
	Without a new economy based on renewable resources, rapid  
deforestation, falling water tables and accelerating climate change 
could undermine economies around the world in the next century, 
said Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	Worldwatch releases its annual report Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
	Unexpected developments just over the past year include a record  
increase in the average global temperature during the year, record 
losses from destructive storms and floods, and the astounding 
number of people displaced by natural disasters -- 300 million, or 
more than the population of North America. The worst disasters were 
in China, Bangladesh and Central America. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would not have been surprised if 1998 was warmer,'' said  
Brown. ``What we didn't expect was that it literally would go off 
the chart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The global average temperature increased 0.2 degrees Celsius or  
more than 0.3 degrees Fahrenheit. That sounds small, but if the 
trend continues into the next century, major global climate 
disruption is expected. 
</P>
<P>
	On the bright side, the report notes huge percentage increases  
in electricity from the wind and the sun. Wind power has increased 
an average of 25.7 percent a year and solar power 16.8 percent a 
year since 1990. Use of renewable energy sources still represents 
only 19 percent of energy use, however, with the bulk from coal, 
oil or natural gas. 
</P>
<P>
	Wind power now provides 7 percent of Denmark's electricity, 23  
percent in northern Spain. The report says just three U.S. states -- 
North and South Dakota and Texas -- could harness enough wind to 
light up the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The report cites predictions made by ``futurists'' in the 1890s  
for this century. They correctly predicted widespread use of 
electricity and telephones, but thought pollution would end and had 
no inkling of the birth control pill, the Internet, two world wars, 
nuclear weapons or the specter of ``a billion people struggling 
just to survive,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmental researcher Christopher Flavin, one of several  
co-authors of the report, said some big surprises can be expected 
in the next century, as well. But the report avoids any outright 
predictions for the next 100 years and certainly not the next 
1,000. 
</P>
<P>
	A major question, he said, is which countries will lead in the  
new technologies. Now, Germany is ahead of the United States in 
development of the $2 billion wind power industry and Japan leads 
in use of solar energy, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing we know for sure is the next century is not  
going to be like the 20th century. We're going to see most trends 
change at some point.'' said Flavin in an interview. Oil 
consumption, water use, and harvesting of needed protein from land 
or sea cannot continue to grow indefinitely, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The need to shift those trends is going to create some  
significant economic disruptions,'' Flavin said, ``and some of the 
biggest investment opportunities.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
