<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Strategy Relies on Lewinsky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House prosecutors relied heavily on Monica  
Lewinsky's credibility to make their impeachment case that 
President Clinton had lied and obstructed justice and to plead for 
trial witnesses to resolve conflicts. 
</P>
<P>
	In a criminal court, such a strategy that highlights  
contradictions would be ``a sure loser,'' a legal expert says. 
</P>
<P>
	But this is not a criminal trial. Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, on  
Saturday called it ``a political process'' before a body divided 
along party lines on the issue of removing Clinton from office. 
</P>
<P>
	The 13 House prosecutors' immediate concern was to win the right  
from senators to go beyond the well-known, voluminous body of 
written evidence to summon witnesses they hope will tip 12 
Democratic senators to the Republican side and win a conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	With their opening trial presentation done, the all-Republican  
prosecution team's drive for witnesses will continue in private -- 
where they must identify specific reasons to call the witnesses and 
convince senators they can keep such a process concise and 
controlled. They were signs Saturday they had gained some support. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not averse to having some limited testimony by a few  
witnesses ... that would help us'' resolve conflicts in testimony, 
said Sen. John Chafee, a moderate Republican from Rhode Island whom 
Democrats had once hoped would help them defeat a vote on 
witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Over three days, the prosecutors delivered to the Senate, in  
painstaking detail, a case alleging a broad conspiracy by Clinton 
to illegally conceal his extramarital affair from Paula Jones' 
lawyers, and then to keep certain embarrassing facts about that 
relationship from a federal grand jury. 
</P>
<P>
	The managers identified a half-dozen alleged lies by Clinton to  
the grand jury and some eight more in his deposition in the Jones 
case. And they identified several other acts they said the 
president committed to hide evidence or influence the testimony of 
other witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	But to make the case, they had to assert that the testimony of  
witnesses such as Ms. Lewinsky and Oval Office Secretary Betty 
Currie, which conflicted with that of the president, was more 
believable. They repeatedly tried to bolster the former intern, 
calling her ``very credible'' and her assertions in past testimony 
``common sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If you believe the testimony of Monica Lewinsky, you cannot  
believe the president,'' Rep. Bill McCollum of Florida argued at 
one point Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Almost by definition, if a case is built on conflicting  
testimony, there is reasonable doubt,'' said John Douglass, a 
former Iran-Contra prosecutor and now a professor of criminal law 
at the University of Richmond. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the criminal world, it's a sure loser to begin with. This  
is a case no prosecutor would ever bring, facing a burden of proof 
beyond a reasonable doubt in front of an unbiased jury,'' Douglass 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the impeachment trial, there is no burden for prosecutors  
to prove their case beyond a reasonable doubt -- since each senator 
determines his or her own standards for conviction or acquittal. 
And a Senate composed of 100 politicians is hardly an unbiased 
jury. 
</P>
<P>
	To win a conviction, the House prosecutors must win 67 votes.  
They have a lesser threshold to meet in winning the right to call 
witnesses, just 51 senators can authorize such a move. 
</P>
<P>
	John Dean, the White House counsel under Richard Nixon who went  
to prison for the Watergate cover-up, said, ``I thought the most 
interesting weakness was the call for witnesses. If they need 
witnesses to make their case, they do not have clear and convincing 
evidence to bring to the Senate. Clear and convincing evidence 
would not call for witnesses to make the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Why then, are the prosecutors pushing so hard for the Senate to  
invite President Clinton to testify, and summon Ms. Lewinsky, Mrs. 
Currie and presidential friend Vernon Jordan? 
</P>
<P>
	``Any trial lawyer will tell you that in the course of a trial,  
stuff happens. If you start calling witnesses, you don't know what 
happens. The dynamic changes. It's an ``X'' factor,'' explained Ira 
Reiner, the Los Angeles district attorney from 1984-92. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:09:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jenny Thompson Sets Swimming Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Five-time Olympic champion Jenny  
Thompson, who shattered two world records last month, broke the 
100-meter individual medley world record at a World Cup 
short-course meet Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson followed up her record-breaking peformance by winning  
the 50-meter butterfly, giving her five gold medals at the meet. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 100 medley, the American knocked 0.02 seconds off the  
short-course world mark set by Slovakian Martina Moravcova one 
month ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson, who also holds the world record in the short-course  
50-meter and 100-meter butterfly which she set in College Station, 
Texas, last month, clocked 1:00.41 to beat Moravcova's 1:00.43. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess I'm on a roll,'' said Thompson, who spent some time  
training in Canberra following a short vacation in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got a winning streak going, and I hope I can keep it  
going forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While at the Australian Institute of Sport in Canberra, Thompson  
spent some time with coach Gennadi Touretski, the Russian who also 
coaches Michael Klim and Alex Popov. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've learned a lot from him,'' Thompson said. ``He has a  
different way of explaining things, and I think his stroke 
technique has helped me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 25-year-old Thompson also won the 100-meter butterfly and  
50-meter freestyle on Friday night and the 50-meter butterfly and 
100-meter freestyle on Saturday, in which she was just .33 seconds 
off the five-year-old world mark. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson won $2,000 from international swimming federation FINA  
for the world record and she is also in the running for another 
$10,000 which is the total prize money to be divided among world 
pace setters during the Australian stop on the short-course series. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Cup moves to Hobart on Monday and Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Officials gave Thompson a small rest after breaking the world  
record so she was able to recover for the 50-meter butterfly. She 
then went out and won in 26.36 -- just 0.31 off her own world 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would have been great but I was just too tired,'' Thompson  
said when asked by a television commentator poolside if she thought 
it was possible to break two world records in consecutive events. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson clocked 53.34 seconds in the 100 meters to beat German  
Katrin Meissner and Alison Sheppard of Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Claim Ambitious Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans have a new leader and an  
ambitious legislative agenda that has nothing to do with 
impeachment, a GOP leader said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our agenda is not a partisan agenda. Rather it is an American  
agenda,'' Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., vice chairwoman of the House 
Republican Conference, said in the Republicans' weekly radio 
address. 
</P>
<P>
	Her remarks echoed pledges from Senate Republicans last week,  
who promised that the impeachment trial under way in the Senate 
will not consume all the legislators' time and energy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to use every minute that we're not in the  
impeachment trial preparing for our legislative agenda,'' Sen. Kay 
Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said shortly after President Clinton's 
trial on allegations of for alleged perjury and obstruction of 
justice began. 
</P>
<P>
	And Fowler's remarks follow meetings last week in her home  
state, at which top Republican donors from across the country 
vented irritation with the party's top leaders and GOP losses in 
the 1998 election. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson heard  
complaints from a few GOP backers at one session Thursday in Palm 
Beach that the party's themes have disappeared into an impeachment 
vacuum. 
</P>
<P>
	David Bardes, one of about 100 ``Eagles'' invited to the  
session, said Nicholson took tough questions in stride. Eagles are 
contributors who donate at least $15,000 annually to the Republican 
Party. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have a right to be concerned as a result of the last  
election,'' said Bardes, who came away from the session encouraged 
about GOP legislative plans. ``I think Nicholson, et al., 
understand that there were mistakes made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In her address, Fowler said the House GOP, under leadership of  
the new speaker, Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., will focus on 
education, Social Security, tax relief and military funding. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me be clear in saying that it is an agenda that will  
succeed only if Congress works together in a bipartisan manner, 
leaving behind the acrimony of last year,'' Fowler said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans are committed to working with Clinton on a number of  
fronts, she said. She also challenged the president, who is 
scheduled to deliver his State of the Union address Tuesday night, 
to follow up on a pledge from last year's speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``President Clinton said that saving Social Security would be  
his top priority,'' Fowler said. ``It is now one year later, and we 
are still waiting.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
