<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast, Midwest Seek Thaw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- First snow, then sleet. Now comes the thaw.  
</P>
<P>
	At least that's what many in the Northeast and Midwest were  
hoping for today after winter storms lashed the region Thursday and 
Friday with every permutation of precipitation -- snow, sleet, rain 
and ice. 
</P>
<P>
	Roofs, especially, were starting to feel the strain after  
nearing 3 feet of snow piled up in some places. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York's Livingston County, a 51-year-old woman was trapped  
for nearly two hours Friday after her carport collapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	A buildup of snow and ice was also blamed for part of a roof  
giving way at a Lockheed Martin manufacturing plant in Syracuse. 
The collapse sent about 20 workers scurrying for safety, but no one 
was hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	And in the Rochester suburb of Penfield, about 200 residents of  
an apartment complex were evacuated Friday when a roof began to 
collapse under the weight of 2 feet of snow. Nobody was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The story was much the same elsewhere in the region.  
</P>
<P>
	In Boston, as the slippery storm changed to ice and then rain,  
cars continued to slide off highways while others plowed through 
foot-deep flooding that swamped roads and forced pedestrians to 
hurdle slush puddles. More than 100 vehicles had to be towed in the 
region, said state police Lt. Paul Maloney. 
</P>
<P>
	In suburbs of Cleveland, snow collapsed a metal greenhouse at a  
market and caved in the garage roof of an apartment complex, 
damaging four cars. No one was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures in the region were expected to rise into the 40s  
and possibly 50s today and stay there through Tuesday, the National 
Weather Service said. 
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't entirely good news -- in some parts of Ohio where the  
snow has started to melt, homeowners could get flooded basements. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have seen a 25 percent increase in our business because of  
the weather,'' said Tony Caserta, manager of Gem City Home 
Improvement and Water Proofing in Dayton. ``All of that rain and 
sleet we have been having has caused an extra amount of water and 
many basements that wouldn't normally leak are leaking now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With about 100 flights canceled out of LaGuardia and Newark  
airports, hundreds of New York Jets fans started screaming ``seats, 
seats, seats'' Friday to get to Denver for Sunday's football game 
against the Broncos. 
</P>
<P>
	``They can't just take a later flight Sunday or Monday because  
the game will be over,'' said United Airlines spokesman Gary 
Lonieski. ``We're getting them out there. We don't want anybody to 
be disappointed.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
