<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Jan. 16, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Support Holding Strong  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite three days of arguments by House  
Republicans in the impeachment trial, there is little evidence that 
President Clinton's Democratic support in the Senate has eroded. 
Although House prosecutors Saturday demanded Clinton's removal from 
office, Democratic Senator from New Jersey Robert Torricelli said 
based on the current record, the prosecutors aren't going to win. 
And one Republican, Vermont Sen. James Jeffords, sounded skeptical 
of the case. ``If you say lying about a non-crime (an affair) can 
be converted into a high crime by the way you handle it, that sets 
a pretty low standard for me,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Massacre Triggers NATO Talks  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department says NATO will hold an  
emergency session Sunday in Brussels to consider a response to the 
execution-style killings of dozens of people in southern Kosovo. 
NATO's contingency plans involve the possible bombing of Serb 
installations. The bodies were found Saturday, shot or mutilated in 
what appears to be the worst slaying in the nearly year-old 
conflict in the separatist province. The discovery came a day after 
Serb forces attacked the area in southern Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Ventura Hosts People's Inaugural  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Gov. Jesse Ventura arrived Saturday night  
wearing pink wraparound sunglasses, a bandana on his bald head, 
three earrings and a Jimi Hendrix T-shirt at an inaugural ball as 
unorthodox as his campaign -- and his supporters -- more than 13,000 
of them -- loved it. ``The Body's back for tonight,'' Ventura said. 
``Thank you, everyone. Let's party Minnesota.'' The inaugural party 
was, in fact, dubbed ``The People's Celebration'' by organizers. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Sanctions Denounced by Saddam  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein denounced  
U.N. sanctions Saturday, saying nothing could compare to their 
``mischief and damage.'' His speech marked the eighth anniversary 
of the outbreak of the 1991 Persian Gulf War in which a U.S.-led 
coalition of forces liberated Kuwait from seven months of Iraqi 
occupation. Earlier, about 6,000 people marched through the center 
of the city in a government-organized demonstration against a U.S. 
proposal to remove the cap on Iraqi oil exports. 

</P>
<P>
	Methodist Ministers Wed Lesbians  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Two lesbians who have been together  
for 15 years exchanged promises on Saturday in a ``holy union'' 
ceremony blessed by more than 90 United Methodist ministers. The 
ceremony before more than one-thousand people was held in defiance 
of a church law against same-sex marriages. The blessing could cost 
the ministers their jobs. California voters next year will decide 
whether only marriages between a man and a woman are legal. 

</P>
<P>
	Venezuela Joins Colombian Talks  
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- President-elect Hugo Chavez of Venezuela traveled  
to Cuba on Saturday for private talks with Fidel Castro and 
Colombian President Andres Pastrana. The talks were expected to 
address attempts to bring peace to Colombia, which has been wracked 
by a 34-year civil conflict. Pastrana, who arrived in Havana for an 
official visit on Thursday, has referred to Chavez's trip to Cuba 
at the same time as ``coincidental.'' But, he has noted that the 
Venezuelan leader had expressed interest in helping end the 
guerrilla war in neighboring Colombia. 

</P>
<P>
	Guilty Plea Involves Super Bowl  
</P>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Robert William Greer agreed to plead  
guilty to murder and go to prison -- but only if he could watch the 
Super Bowl before being sent up. Greer, a Minnesota Vikings fan, 
asked that he be allowed to watch the game at the Tarrant County 
jail -- and then be shipped off the day after. Prosecutors agreed to 
the deal, and Greer was sentenced to serve 18 years. 

</P>
<P>
	Maple Leafs 4, Flyers 3  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Steve Sullivan scored two goals and Derek  
King had the game winner as the Toronto Maple Leafs halted 
Philadelphia's 15-game unbeaten streak with a 4-3 victory over the 
Flyers on tonight. King's goal, his 16th, came after stopping the 
puck that had caromed wide of the net, and firing a slap shot from 
the left circle past John Vanbiesbrouck with 5:19 left in the third 
period. It was the first Flyers' defeat since a 5-4 loss on Dec. 10 
to New Jersey. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 11 St. John's 88, Rutgers 78  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lavor Postell scored 16 of his 21 points in the  
second half and No. 11 St. John's pulled away over the final four 
minutes for an 88-78 victory over Rutgers on tonight. The Red Storm 
(15-3, 6-1 Big East) won for the 12th time in 13 games and for the 
14th straight time at home. Rutgers (10-6, 3-4) lost for the fourth 
time in fifth game. 


</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JAKE ULICK  
</P>
</TEXT>
