<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thompson Wins 100-Meter Freestyle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Five-time Olympic champion Jenny  
Thompson broke the women's world 100-meter medley short-course 
record today at a World Cup swim meet. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson bettered a one-month-old record set by Slovakia's  
Martina Moravcova by two one-hundredths of a second in the 25-meter 
pool at the Sydney International Aquatic Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson won in 1 minute, 00.41 seconds to set the first world  
record of the two-day meet. Earlier she won the 100-meter freestyle 
earlier, and on Friday took the 100-meter butterfly and 50-meter 
freestyle. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson clocked 53.34 seconds in the 100-meter freestyle to  
beat German Katrin Meissner and Alison Sheppard of Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson hinted she was on track to break the long-standing  
world record of 53.01, set in 1993 by China's Le Jingyi, at the 
next World Cup in Hobart beginning Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't feel very spectacular, but my time was my best time,  
so I was happy with that,'' Thompson said after the 100 freestyle. 
``Maybe in Hobart I'll go faster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	South African Penny Heyns made it two wins in two races, again  
beating Australia's Samantha Riley to take her second breaststroke 
event at the meet. 
</P>
<P>
	Heyns won the 50-meter sprint in 31.29 seconds, with Helen  
Denman of Australia second in 31.27, and Riley third in 31.81. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Heyns won the 100-meter breaststroke ahead of Riley.  
</P>
<P>
	Australia's Ian Thorpe won the 200-meter freestyle in 1 minute,  
46.35 seconds, overtaking Italy's Massi Rosolino by a half second 
late in the race. Australia's Grant Hackett was third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
