<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minnie Pearl Auction Draws Faithful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Hundreds of diehard country music fans  
bid on the belongings of the late Minnie Pearl on Saturday, vying 
for mementos of the Grand Ole Opry legend known for her big grin 
and shrill ``Howdeeeee!'' 
</P>
<P>
	``She was one of the best,'' Gary Allgood said after paying $350  
for one of Miss Pearl's trademark straw hats, with its wide brim 
and $1.98 price tag dangling from the side. 
</P>
<P>
	Allgood and his wife, Verla, drove 14 hours from Houston for the  
auction. They saw Miss Pearl perform in 1967 at the Grand Ole Opry. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just country people. We love country music,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	More than 900 pieces went on the auction block to settle the  
estate of Minnie Pearl, whose real name was Sarah Cannon. She died 
in 1996 at the age of 83 after more than half a century on the 
Grand Ole Opry and 20 years on the syndicated television show ``Hee 
Haw.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her husband, Henry Cannon, died one year later. The couple had  
no children. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the items on the auction block were jewelry, furniture  
and knickknacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of history here,'' auctioneer Lester Arutt said.  
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate estimate Saturday on how much money was  
bid at the auction. 
</P>
<P>
	Rich Hufnagel, 53, of Goodlettsville, picked up a color  
photograph of Miss Pearl with several other country music stars. He 
once got a hug from Miss Pearl while she signed autographs at her 
store on Music Row. 
</P>
<P>
	``She gave a really nice hug,'' Hufnagel said.  
</P>
<P>
	Beth Hall, 51, of Smryna, who saw Miss Pearl perform 31 years  
ago at the Opry, said the auction was an appropriate way to dispose 
of Miss Pearl's belongings, because the fans would treasure them as 
much as any relative could. 
</P>
<P>
	``Minnie would be happy about this,'' Hall said. ``Minnie would  
look at this as her last audience. These people wouldn't be here if 
they didn't love her.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 01:12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Stocks Soar; Currency Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Stock markets responded with  
euphoria to Brazil's decision to let its currency float, the latest 
strategy aimed at lifting Latin America's largest economy out of 
the doldrums. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil announced Friday it would temporarily stop using its cash  
reserves to prop up its beleaguered currency, the real. Investors 
took this to mean that interest rates would fall and stimulate new 
investment. 
</P>
<P>
	``This week alone some billions of dollars left the country and  
I am obliged to defend the real,'' President Fernando Henrique 
Cardoso said, explaining his decision in a televised speech on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The devaluation will reduce the doubt in relation to our  
economy and create the conditions to lower interest rates,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	After Brazil's Central Bank announced it would no longer prop up  
the currency, the real plunged as low as 1.60 to the dollar before 
strengthening slightly to 1.43 at the close of trading. That was 
down from 1.32 at the close of trading Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks across the globe headed in the opposite direction,  
however, and the Sao Paulo Stock Exchange -- Latin America's largest 
-- closed up 33.4 percent Friday, all but wiping out the 33.5 
percent it lost in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	But with the devaluation taken into account, the gain in dollar  
terms was nearly cut in half, to 16.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The move effectively floated the real -- if only for one day -- a  
more dramatic step after the Central Bank tried a smaller 
devaluation of 8 percent on Wednesday. The bank made that 
devaluation by extending the band in which the currency could trade 
to between 1.20 reals and 1.32 reals to the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The Central Bank usually enforces the bands by intervening in  
foreign exchange markets to sell its dollar reserves to bolster the 
currency's value. 
</P>
<P>
	In another move to calm the waters, Claudio Mauch, the Central  
Bank's director for financial system supervision, said Friday he 
would stay on in his post. His abrupt resignation a day earlier had 
caused further turmoil in the market. 
</P>
<P>
	The global financial crisis hit Brazil in August, when investors  
pulled money out in fear that the government couldn't cover a $65 
billion budget deficit and might default on loans. Since then, more 
than $40 billion has left the country, dropping reserves to around 
$35 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts cheered the Central Bank's move Friday, saying its  
earlier, more controlled devaluation had been smaller than what 
many economists thought necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	``Controlled devaluations never work when expectations are  
negative,'' said Carlos Langoni, a former Central Bank president. 
With Friday's step, ``the government is taking a more realistic 
attitude toward foreign exchange.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the action, analysts say Brazil's troubles aren't over.  
Economists at Bankers' Trust said the devaluation would increase 
the country's deficit, which Brazil has pledged to decrease under 
an agreement with the International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	And the government-run Institute of Applied Economic Research  
says inflation is almost certain to rise. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, the government agreed to budget reductions in  
exchange for a $41.5 billion aid package put together by the IMF. 
Making those cuts will be harder now because with the devaluation, 
the same tax revenue in reals will mean less in dollar terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Minister Pedro Malan and new Central Bank chief  
Francisco Lopes traveled to Washington on Friday night to discuss 
the new policy with U.S. and IMF officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
