<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Utah Agonizes Over Image-Tarnishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- With statehood shimmering on a distant  
horizon, Brigham Young stood before his embattled Mormon followers 
and spoke candidly of bribing federal officials ``to grease the 
wheels.'' Young justified catering to corruption in 1861 to serve a 
higher cause -- protecting the faith's polygamists while gaining 
support for statehood. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, that rationale resonates down the decades as the city  
Young founded on the edge of the Great Basin agonizes over the 
Olympic bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is something in Mormonism that we're willing to make  
compromises politically to achieve what we want to do, and I can 
see Mormons doing that,'' says Elbert Peck, editor and publisher of 
Sunstone, an independent Mormon periodical. ``I mean, we were 
willing to pay bribes to get statehood.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michael R. Otterson, the church's director of media relations,  
took strong exception to Peck's statement, saying that ``to infer 
that there is something inherent in our faith that espouses 
anything other than the highest ethical and moral standards is 
irresponsible and blatantly false.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With four investigations -- by the Justice Department, the city,  
and the national and international Olympic committees -- trying to 
determine if the 2002 Winter Games were bought and sold, Utahns are 
painfully aware their longed-for debut on the global stage has 
taken a doozy of a pratfall. 
</P>
<P>
	``This type of behavior is not according to the standards of  
this community,'' Gov. Mike Leavitt told a national television 
audience last week. ``We revolt at being even associated with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The governor's sentiments about the still-unfolding scandal are  
shared by many of Utah's more than 2 million inhabitants, 70 
percent of whom, like Leavitt, are members of The Church of Jesus 
Christ of Latter-day Saints. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Garff, chairman of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee and  
a longtime local church leader, says he feels angry ``because our 
reputation is damaged.'' He feels sad ``that every dream we all had 
of bringing the world to our doorstep and being gracious hosts now 
is at risk, and those dreams have been popped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For an image-conscious faith of 10 million members that has  
58,000 missionaries knocking on doors in 123 countries and 
territories, the seamy headlines are a painful reminder that almost 
everyone outside Utah and its immediate neighbors sees Salt Lake 
City and the Mormon heartland as one and the same. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way public opinion and image work, it's not what happened  
so much as what people think happened,'' says Jan Shipps, a noted 
historian of Mormonism. ``And the identity of Salt Lake City with 
the Latter-day Saints and the church means that this is something, 
for better or worse, the church will have to overcome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Publicly, the faith's hierarchy and the city's Olympic boosters  
have kept their distance over the years, neither wanting the 2002 
Games to be perceived as the Mormon Olympics. Some see that as a 
charade, since most of the boosters are influential Mormons. 
</P>
<P>
	Businesses owned by the Mormon church gave $210,938 of the $15  
million raised by Salt Lake's Olympic Bid Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's no secret the church has viewed this thing as a  
proselytizing opportunity and opportunity to show that Mormons 
aren't as weird as people think,'' says Stephen Pace, a community 
activist and longtime critic of the Olympics push. 
</P>
<P>
	Church President Gordon B. Hinckley, architect of the church's  
vast public relations network, has labored long to burnish the 
faith's image as a world religion far removed from its peculiar and 
polygamous roots. 
</P>
<P>
	Basking in the enormous success of the church's media-friendly  
150th anniversary reenactment of the Mormon trek to Utah in 1997, 
Hinckley sat for an interview with Shipps, who asked then about the 
2002 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Hinckley said the church hierarchy was divided over Salt Lake's  
effort to bring the Olympics to town. He declined to disclose his 
own opinion but said once the bid was won the church felt 
``honored.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Salt Lake City will be on the map for those few days across  
the world,'' he told Shipps. ``This is the headquarters of the 
church and it is going to be a great thing. And it is a great 
opportunity for us and we must seize that opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As it happened, the scandal broke Nov. 25, just 10 days after  
the church's governing First Presidency told members the church 
supported Utah's Olympic efforts and called attention to the need 
for volunteers. 
</P>
<P>
	As the scandal has escalated, the church has had little to say  
beyond a one-paragraph statement that says the affair should be 
addressed by the local and international Olympic organizations and 
the ``various investigative bodies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It goes without saying that the church would hope and expect  
that high moral and ethical standards would be applied in any 
aspect of the Salt Lake Olympics,'' the statement says. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Salt Lake City Mayor Ted Wilson, a political scientist  
and Mormon, sees his fellow adherents as ``still a strange 
people,'' with two elements underlying the collective psyche. 
</P>
<P>
	``One is sort of holier-than-thou. We believe that we are kind  
of a righteous, holy people,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	The other, he says, comes from the Mormons' refugee pioneer  
heritage. After all, it's been only a century since the bitter 
battles with the federal government over polygamy, which the church 
abandoned in 1890, and statehood, which came six years later. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a sense of a need for international validation or  
national validation, and I think that's at risk right now,'' Wilson 
says. ``If we fail now because of this big faux pas, I think Utahns 
are going to be very upset and really hurting.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Holds Rare Saturday Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- These days, it takes a rare and momentous  
occasion, such as President Clinton's impeachment trial, for the 
Senate to pull itself together for a Saturday session in the middle 
of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't always the case.  
</P>
<P>
	Such meetings were common in the 19th century and became rarer  
only after the airplane made it easier for senators to escape the 
capital for weekend trips to their home states. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Saturday, the third and final day of presentations by  
House lawmakers making the case for Clinton's removal from office, 
the presence of all senators who could be there was required. 
</P>
<P>
	It could just as well have been a regular weekday session.  
</P>
<P>
	The senators, 98 of the 100, were seated at their mahogany  
desks, wearing business suits and, for the men, ties. Some listened 
intently, arms folded across their chests. Others took copious 
notes or read papers from white binders. 
</P>
<P>
	Sens. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, and John McCain, R-Ariz.,  
returned home, Inouye to attend a funeral, McCain a memorial 
service, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The chamber was silent except for a few stray coughs, the buzz  
of blown noses, the rustling of papers and the microphone-enhanced 
voices of the House lawmakers speaking from a lectern in the well 
of the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Pages busied themselves delivering notes and envelopes to the  
senators, along with boxes of tissue and glasses of water as staff 
ushered members of the public into and out of the visitors' 
galleries overhead. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate might meet again next Saturday to continue  
questioning of both parties in the case. And if the Senators 
ultimately decide to hear from witnesses, they could spend many 
more Saturdays in session. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1800s, it was Congress' practice to spend half the year  
in the nation's capital and the other in their home states. The 
time constraints often required Saturday sessions, said Donald 
Ritchie, the Senate's associate historian. 
</P>
<P>
	As late as the 1950s, even when not in session, it was not  
unusual for senators and their staffs to work in their offices on 
Saturdays, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The turning point came in 1958. The first transcontinental  
airplanes were introduced, and ``for the first time, senators from 
almost any state could go home on weekends, even from California,'' 
Ritchie said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under pressure from members who wanted to spend weekends at  
home, Senate leaders agreed not to schedule votes on Monday 
mornings or Friday afternoons, Ritchie said. The practice has 
remained unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The last really grave issue that forced a Saturday meeting early  
in a congressional year was the question of whether the United 
States should follow through with threats of force to drive Iraq's 
occupying army from Kuwait. The Senate met for nearly nine hours 
Jan. 12, 1991, before voting 52-47 to endorse the use of force. 
</P>
<P>
	Not war but money almost always is the reason for weekend Senate  
sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Usually it's the end of the budget year, and spending bills to  
keep the government functioning must be approved. Senate leaders 
bent on adjourning by a specific date will stretch the regular 
workweek to Saturday, Ritchie said. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of fights over money and the subsequent shutdown of the  
federal government, senators met on one Saturday in November 1995 
and on three consecutive Saturdays the following month. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty years ago, President Carter's proposals to handle the  
energy crisis prompted a marathon Senate session that began on 
Saturday, Oct. 14, 1978, and ended when lawmakers recessed at 7:16 
p.m. on Oct. 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How the Jets and Broncos Match Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Matchups for Sunday's AFC title game between the 	
New York Jets and Denver Broncos:	
</P>
<P>
                      *WHEN THE JETS HAVE THE BALL 	
</P>
<P>
	Just as they did against Jacksonville, the Jets want to control  
the clock and keep Denver's potent offense off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	That means Curtis Martin (28), who had 36 carries vs. the  
Jaguars, will be busy again, particularly if the game is close. 
Martin has power and speed, although he isn't quite in the class of 
Terrell Davis (30). Martin also is dangerous on screen passes. 
</P>
<P>
	Vinny Testaverde (16) led the AFC in passing and has been  
protected well by a surprisingly solid, mistake-free line led by 
center Kevin Mawae (68), rookie tackle Jason Fabini (69) and 
veteran tackle Jumbo Elliott (76). The line will be tested by 
Denver's Trevor Pryce (93) and Maa Tanuvasa (98) up front -- both 
had 8.5 sacks -- and zone blitzes featuring linebackers Bill 
Romanowski (53), Glenn Cadrez (59), a former Jet, and John Mobley 
(51). 
</P>
<P>
	Testaverde has displayed poise and a surprising nimbleness when  
forced out of the pocket. He rarely forces his throws, which was a 
past problem, and has many weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Keyshawn Johnson (19) has become an all-purpose threat at  
wideout, running every kind of route, catching high, low and 
in-between passes, blocking and handling end-arounds. He matches up 
well with Denver defensive backs, who might struggle with his size 
(6-foot-3, 212). Only safety Steve Atwater (27) is comparable, and 
he doesn't have the speed to stay with Johnson. Backup cornerback 
Tory James (20), who is 6-1 and 195, might see more action. 
</P>
<P>
	Wayne Chrebet (80) also runs every type of pattern and is most  
dangerous on third downs out of the slot. If Johnson consistently 
draws double-teams, Chrebet or speedy Dedric Ward (89) could become 
major factors. Denver does not have a strong secondary, although 
cornerbacks Ray Crockett (39) and Darrien Gordon (21) are 
aggressive. 
</P>
<P>
	Tight end Kyle Brady (88) has been an effective blocker and is  
vastly improved as a receiver. But he dropped two passes last 
Sunday against Jacksonville. 
</P>
<P>
	Two veterans who might make a difference are fullback Keith  
Byars (41), a steady blocker and fine receiver, and David Meggett 
(22), who has been most effective as a pass-catcher. 
</P>
<P>
                    *WHEN THE BRONCOS HAVE THE BALL   	
</P>
<P>
	Davis is the most formidable offensive weapon in football. He  
proved that once again with 199 yards rushing and two TDs against 
Miami last Saturday. Not only is he a 2,000-yard runner with power, 
speed, moves and moxie, but Davis is a first-rate receiver who 
averaged 8.7 yards a catch during his MVP season. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York's favor is its strong group of linebackers, led by  
All-Pro Mo Lewis (57) and Bryan Cox (51). Both are versatile and 
will draw much of Davis' attention. 
</P>
<P>
	But Davis has faced many excellent linebackers this year,  
including All-Pro Zach Thomas last Saturday, and still been a 
dominant performer. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver's line is one of the league's best, even without  
perennial Pro Bowl tackle Gary Zimmerman, who retired before the 
season. Center Tom Nalen (66) is just as good as Mawae and will 
work against a pair of overachieving tackles, Ernie Logan (93) and 
Jason Ferguson (72), most of the time. Guard Mark Schlereth (69) 
and tackle Tony Jones (77) are formidable veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets will attempt to confuse the Broncos with their  
defensive schemes, but John Elway (7) has seen everything -- and 
generally dealt with everything -- in his superb career. Elway 
showed he still can scramble against Miami, but look for him to 
work medium-range to All-Pro tight end Shannon Sharpe (88) and 
Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the most intriguing matchup is Pro Bowl WR Ed McCaffrey  
(87) and fellow receiver Rod Smith (80) against cornerbacks Aaron 
Glenn (31), Otis Smith (45) and Ray Mickens (24). Glenn, a Pro 
Bowler, returned last Sunday from a sprained ankle, but is not 100 
percent, which means Mickens might move over from the slot. 
Regardless, Denver will try to get R. Smith deep against O. Smith, 
who had a good year, but was beaten for two scores by Jacksonville. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver scored an AFC-high 501 points and has moved the ball at  
home against everyone. Elway's skill at reading defenses and the 
line's ability to pick up stunts and blitzes provide the Broncos 
with a solid edge. 
</P>
<P>
                           *SPECIAL TEAMS   	
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, the Jets had one of the top three special teams in  
the league. Not now. They've been vulnerable to runbacks, 
particularly on punt returns, where opponents have a 3-yard edge. 
Jacksonville broke an 88-yard kickoff return last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	While returners Meggett, Kevin Williams (23) and Ward haven't  
been big-time threats -- the Jets miss injured Leon Johnson, even 
though he was inconsistent this season -- placekicker John Hall (9) 
has gotten steadier. He nailed a 52-yarder last Sunday and his 
kickoffs generally get to the end zone. Hall has overcome much of 
close-range problems this year. 
</P>
<P>
	John Kidd (17), New York's third punter of 1998, was the best of  
the lot, but nothing special. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Rouen (16) is one of football's best punters and Denver's  
coverage has been good. Gordon always ranks among the league's top 
punt returners, and Vaughn Hebron (22) was third in the AFC with a 
26.4 kickoff return average. Hebron returned a kickoff 95 yards for 
a touchdown this season, Denver's first kickoff return for a score 
since 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Elam (1) made the Pro Bowl after another terrific year. He  
tied Tom Dempsey's record with a 63-yard field goal and scored 127 
points (23-for-27 on FGs, 58-for-58 on PATs). His deep kickoffs 
aided a solid coverage unit. 
</P>
<P>
                             *COACHING   	
</P>
<P>
	A wash.  
</P>
<P>
	Bill Parcells has been to three Super Bowls and won two, and his  
work in turning around one of NFL's worst franchises has been 
remarkable. His staff, led by defensive coordinator Bill Belichick 
and offensive coordinator Charlie Weis, favors aggressive, 
innovative schemes that make the best use of New York's personnel. 
Parcells also knows how to challenge his players and how to keep 
them at their best. 
</P>
<P>
	So does Mike Shanahan, who did a wonderful job taking the  
Broncos from wild card to NFL champion last season, then not 
allowing them to lose focus in 1998. The fact they couldn't go 
undefeated became insignificant when they righted themselves the 
last two weeks. Shanahan is just as inventive as his Jets 
counterparts and won't panic. Plus, he has the better team. 
</P>
<P>
                           *INTANGIBLES   	
</P>
<P>
	While Parcells and his coaches have been this route before, and  
he has 19 players with previous playoff experience, these Jets 
haven't been to a title game together. They made some errors 
against Jacksonville that would be more costly against the Broncos. 
</P>
<P>
	But New York also won some big road games and such key players  
as Testaverde, Martin, Byars, Cox, Pepper Johnson and Elliott are 
pressure-tested. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, the Broncos have been through every challenge -- and  
conquered them -- in the last two years. They haven't lost at home 
since the 1996 playoffs. The environment at Mile High Stadium can 
only help them. 
</P>
<P>
	If it comes down to talent, location and recent history, Denver  
has the edge. But if it's a matter of destiny ... . 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 15:08:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U S West, Olympics Back Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Things got better Saturday for the  
beleaguered Salt Lake Organizing Committee -- better by $5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the amount of a check U S West president Sol Trujillo  
handed to SLOC chairman Robert Garff. It had been held up amid the 
scandal over Salt Lake Olympic boosters' lavish wooing of 
International Olympic Committee members. 
</P>
<P>
	And, from Switzerland, president Juan Antonio Samaranch said the  
IOC might step in to help the 2002 Winter Games cope with any 
financial shortfall. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with the newspaper Le Temps, Samaranch indicated  
some flexibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``We signed a contract, and each partner should in principle  
abide by that,'' he said. ``It depends on what help Salt Lake City 
wants. We will find a solution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch also told the newspaper that the IOC executive board  
probably will decide next week to ban member visits to cities 
bidding for the Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Trujillo, flanked by Gov. Mike Leavitt and Garff at a press  
conference, said he was impressed with Salt Lake's efforts to get 
to the bottom of corruption, expose it and get on with the business 
of staging the games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're investing significant dollars and we expect to have the  
kinds of results associated with the sponsorship,'' Trujillo said. 
``There has been candor and forthrightness. I believe this state is 
stepping up to the values and principles of the Olympics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, U S West said it was withholding a $5  
million payment -- part of the company's $60 million cash and inkind 
services commitment -- until it had assurances the scandal would not 
interfere with the games. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC's two top executives resigned Jan. 8, two others were  
put on administrative leave and the man who led the bid effort, Tom 
Welch, was stripped of his consulting contract and pension. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Garff beamed as he held the check, made out to  
Olympic Properties of the United States, the joint venture of the 
SLOC and the United States Olympic Company to raise sponsorship 
revenue for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is that a welcome sight?'' he asked.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is symbolic of what will happen when integrity is  
restored to the games,'' Garff said. ``It's symbolic in every way 
of the good times ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garff said he remains confident the 2002 Winter Games will raise  
all the money it needs from sponsors. It already has commitments 
for 75 percent of the $1.4 billion budget. Another $250 million 
must yet be raised from sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor said Saturday that he has had calls from many  
existing sponsors, and they are sticking with Salt Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch has not explicitly agreed to help Salt Lake if  
sponsors shy away, Leavitt said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I sense they are prepared to do so,'' he said. ``They share  
responsibility in this. It's appropriate that they do (help).'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The actions of U S West make it very clear we're moving one  
direction -- forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he doesn't know when an independent SLOC ethics panel  
will finish its investigation, but ``the truth will be put on the 
table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll make it very clear what happened with full detail,''  
Leavitt said. ``All our knowledge will be disclosed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ethics panel is conducting one of four investigations. The  
others are by the IOC, USOC and the Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	In the newspaper interview Saturday, Samaranch reiterated that  
he believed that a smaller committee -- and not the full IOC 
membership -- should be responsible for awarding the games in the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	``The IOC has tried to change its voting system,'' he said.  
``But it's very difficult to convince members to give up their 
rights. We're now going to try again. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone is awaiting the decisions of Jan. 24. If we prove  
then that we are determined to clean up, then the worst of the 
crisis will be over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any changes in the system would be in place before the selection  
in June of the 2006 Winter Games site. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch told The Associated Press in an interview Thursday  
that he has written to 13 members implicated in its inquiry into 
cash payments, scholarships, free medical care and other favors 
accepted during the course of Salt Lake City's successful bid for 
the 2002 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine risk expulsion and four face lesser sanctions, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	In other developments:  
</P>
<P>
	-- FBI investigators have approached several escort services  
seeking information about whether Salt Lake bid boosters bought 
prostitutes for IOC members, The Salt Lake Tribune reported. Salt 
Lake attorney Gerald Mooney said the escort services he represents 
are refusing to release records unless compelled by law to do so. 
Such services are legal in Utah if properly registered as a 
sexually oriented business, and many advertise as dating services. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Former Atlanta mayor and United Nations ambassador Andrew  
Young told The Atlanta Journal-Constitution there was no bribery 
involved in Atlanta's Olympic bid for the 1996 Summer Games. 
Humanitarianism, not bribery, motivated Atlanta's assistance to 
Third World athletes and Olympic officials before and after the 
1996 Games, Young told the newspaper for Saturday's editions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Absolutely no money changed hands,'' he said of Atlanta's  
winning bid. ``We raised money, we raised it openly, we discussed 
it publicly. It's inconceivable to me that Atlanta (dealings), 
prior to the bid, could be conceived as a bribe to get the 
Olympics,'' he said in Saturday's editions of the newspaper. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
