<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Impeachment Crisis Began a Year Ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A year ago this weekend, President Clinton  
rode in his limousine to his lawyer's offices in downtown 
Washington and spent close to six hours answering questions about 
events stretching back to his days as governor of Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	That weekend changed everything. Most Americans -- Clinton among  
them -- were unaware of events that had been set in motion that 
would embarrass him before the world and put him on trial before 
the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's press secretary had shrugged off the sexual harassment  
lawsuit brought by former Arkansas state worker Paula Jones as ``a 
distraction but ... not a burdensome distraction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton would soon know just how distracting, and how  
burdensome, this matter would become. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday newspapers reported on the president's testimony. The  
Associated Press said Clinton had been given ``the inglorious 
distinction of the first American president to testify as a 
defendant in any criminal or civil suit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Going in, he had been unaware he would be confronted by  
questions about a former intern, a pert young woman from 
California, Monica Lewinsky. Leaving, he had to know that his life 
had taken a fateful twist. 
</P>
<P>
	How it unfolded:  
</P>
<P>
	Friday, Jan. 16: Tipped off by Pentagon worker Linda Tripp and  
her secret tape recordings, Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr 
gets permission to make a federal case of the president's affair 
and alleged cover-up. Starr's agents act quickly, knowing that 
Newsweek magazine is working on a story that could tip their hand. 
</P>
<P>
	They confront Ms. Lewinsky as she arrives in the vast, airy food  
court of a local mall for lunch with her friend, Mrs. Tripp. They 
take her to a ritzy hotel room, where prosecutors pressed the 
tearful 24-year-old until almost midnight, urging her to help prove 
the president was obstructing justice. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Mrs. Tripp shares her information about the affair  
with Paula Jones' attorneys on the eve of the long-awaited 
presidential deposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday, Jan. 17: Unaware of Starr's actions, Clinton arrives  
to testify, and is caught off guard by numerous, detailed questions 
about Ms. Lewinsky. He stammers and hesitates. Under oath, he 
denies that they had ``sexual relations'' and says he doesn't 
remember being alone with her. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time the presidential limousine headed back to the White  
House at 4:20 p.m., ``He knew that someone was talking,'' said 
David Schippers, chief Republican investigator on the House 
Judiciary Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The next morning, much of Washington knew it, too -- thanks to a  
then-obscure Internet site known as the Drudge Report, which said 
Newsweek was sitting on a blockbuster story about the president's 
affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was no longer a popular president settling comfortably  
into his second term, tinkering with his legacy for the history 
books. He was a president in crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Three days later, on Wednesday morning, Jan. 21, newspapers and  
TV broadcasts brought the nation the story that would dominate the 
news in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	January: Pundits boldly predict Clinton will resign within days.  
With the first lady standing by his side, the embattled president 
jabs his finger at a cluster of reporters and TV cameras and 
declares, ``I did not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss 
Lewinsky. I never told anybody to lie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	March: Another woman tells her story. In an interview on CBS'  
``60 Minutes,'' former White House aide Kathleen Willey says 
Clinton made a sexual advance inside the Oval Office suite in 1993 
when she came to him at a moment of personal crisis, seeking a job. 
</P>
<P>
	April: A federal judge dismisses the Jones lawsuit. Mrs. Jones  
appeals, and Clinton eventually will settle the suit out of court 
for $850,000 without admitting wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	July: After months of stalemate, Ms. Lewinsky agrees to  
cooperate with Starr in exchange for immunity from prosecution. She 
turns over a critical piece of evidence: a dress stained during an 
intimate encounter with the president. And after eight days of 
grand jury testimony Mrs. Tripp, who secretly tape-recorded her 
friend's conversations that disclosed the affair and alleged 
cover-up, emerges from the courthouse and tells Americans, ``I'm 
just like you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	August: Ms. Lewinsky breaks her silence before Starr's grand  
jury. Clinton follows on Aug. 17, testifying by videotape from the 
White House. For the first time, he admits ``inappropriate intimate 
contact.'' But other statements during his testimony will later be 
condemned as perjury by the House. Clinton goes on national 
television to acknowledge an inappropriate relationship that was 
``a personal failure on my part.'' The White House backdrop for his 
speech is carefully arranged by a Hollywood producer. 
</P>
<P>
	September: Starr sends the House of Representatives a report  
alleging ``substantial and credible information ... that may 
constitute grounds for impeachment.'' The House posts the report, 
including its details of the presidential sex life, on the 
Internet. Bookstores sell out of copies of the report. Its tawdry 
details become fodder for late-night comedians. Amid dire 
predictions from the pundits, the four-hour videotape of the 
president's grand jury testimony is televised nationally. Yet, 
Clinton's poll numbers go up. 
</P>
<P>
	October: The House votes 258-176 on Oct. 8 to open an  
impeachment inquiry. Merchants say the most popular Halloween 
costumes are Monica Lewinsky and Bill Clinton masks. 
</P>
<P>
	November: Democrats pick up five House seats, a blow to  
Republicans who believed the election would increase their 
majority. Exit polls show almost two-thirds of voters don't want 
Clinton impeached. White House aides speculate that the momentum 
toward impeachment has faltered. Democrats attack Starr's tactics 
at a House Judiciary Committee hearing. But Republicans are furious 
over Clinton's evasive responses to their 81 questions about his 
conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	December: The House Judiciary Committee approves four articles  
of impeachment accusing Clinton of perjury, obstruction of justice 
and abuse of power. Republican House leaders block Democratic 
efforts to schedule an alternative vote on censure. On the eve of 
the House debate on the impeachment articles, Clinton orders air 
strikes on Iraq. Some Republicans cry foul, but the vote is 
postponed. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since 1868, the House votes Dec. 19 mostly  
along party lines to impeach Clinton on two articles alleging 
perjury before the grand jury and obstruction of justice in the 
Jones case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 18:10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Epic Honor Wins Golden Date Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, Calif. (AP) -- Epic Honor ran down entrymate Blue Tune in  
the stretch and then pulled away in a driving finish to win 
Saturday's $150,000 Golden Gate Derby by a length and a half. 
</P>
<P>
	Trained by Jeff Bonde and ridden by Lonnie Meche, Epic Honor  
came off a six-week layoff to earn the $90,000 first prize while 
covering the 1 1-16 miles in 1:43.58. 
</P>
<P>
	In the process, the colt stamped himself as one of Northern  
California's top 3-year olds by winning the early test for aspiring 
Triple Crown candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``The colt had some hard races so we backed off him,'' said  
Bonde, whose entry finished 1-2 in the eight-horse field. ``But the 
time off did him good. He's been training really nicely and today 
he showed he can come back from a break and do well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blue Tune, ridden by Russell Baze, had forced the pace with  
Absolute Harmony and went in front at the top of the stretch, only 
to be worn down by his stablemate. 
</P>
<P>
	``The horse ran a great race,'' Baze said. ``He didn't switch  
leads again down the lane and that made a little difference. A 
horse gets a little tired racing on his left lead all the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bonde said both Epic Honor and Blue Tune may run in the El  
Camino Real Derby at Bay Meadows on March 6, the next major 
Kentucky Derby prep race in Northern California. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is definitely the biggest win I've ever had,'' said  
Bonde, who has been training in the area for 25 years. ``Both of my 
horses ran well today and as a trainer, that's all you can ask for. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even in defeat, I'm happy with Blue Tune but he's going to  
have to change leads to get to the next level. Epic Honor finished 
with a lot of enthusiasm and that's what it's going to take to 
compete in the races down the road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Long shot Brave Gun rallied to take third. The odds-on entry of  
Absolute Harmony and Voice of Destiny, who between them had won 
their last five races, finished out of the money. 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't fire at all,'' said Adalberto Lopez, Absolute  
Harmony's rider. ``He never felt comfortable and didn't relax. It 
was just one of those days. Nothing went right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Voice of Destiny, who won three straight races, including the  
California Juvenile at Bay Meadows on Nov. 14, was coming off a 
two-month layoff due to a foot injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``The time off may have affected him,'' said his rider, Rafael  
Meza. ``He gave me a little run and then started struggling. You 
have to throw away this race. His attitude wasn't quite the same.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Epic Honor and Blue Tune coupled in the wagering, the entry  
returned $9 to win, $9.60 to place and $5.40 to show. Brave Gun 
returned $13.80 to show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 15:42:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fugitives Caught at Mexican Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Two men wanted in a bank robbery and the  
shootings of a Louisiana car salesman and Iowa police chief were 
apprehended by U.S. Customs agents at the Mexican border. 
</P>
<P>
	Timothy Taylor and Michael Taylor, both 20 and unrelated, were  
detained Friday when they tried to re-enter the United States after 
being turned back from Mexico because they did not have proper 
identification. 
</P>
<P>
	The two are accused of killing the salesman Jan. 7 in  
Shreveport, La., robbing a bank in Lamoni in southern Iowa the next 
day and shooting Lamoni police Chief Dale Killpack in the eye as he 
chased them. 
</P>
<P>
	Killpack is recovering from surgery to remove his right eye.  
</P>
<P>
	The two were denied bond during a hearing in front of a judge  
Saturday and remained at a Laredo jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Customs officials said Timothy Taylor had $87,898 in a backpack  
he carried while Michael Taylor had $38,496 in his pants pockets. 
Agents also confiscated a knife and two samurai swords. 
</P>
<P>
	Car salesman Chester Howell, 56, was shot and left to die while  
taking the Taylors on a test drive, police said. Mary Howell said 
she hopes to get answers about her husband's death. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I really want to know, and I'll probably get a  
nonsensical answer, is why they felt they had to kill him,'' she 
said. ``There were other people who could identify them. He would 
have said, `Take the car and go.' To kill him for a $2,500 car -- 
pointless.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 16:12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lafayette To Keep Football Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EASTON, Pa. (AP) -- Lafayette College's board of trustees voted  
Saturday to save the school's 116-year-old football program, remain 
in Division I, and keep its Patriot League affiliation. 
</P>
<P>
	Trustees were considering several options to make Lafayette  
sports more competitive, including dropping football or moving to 
Division III. Either option could have ended the nation's oldest 
college football rivalry between Lafayette and Lehigh, which have 
played 134 times since 1884. 
</P>
<P>
	The college will keep all 23 of its varsity sports and undertake  
a fund-raising effort in support of its athletic programs, the 
trustees decided in a special vote in New York that concluded a 
three-month study of the college's sports programs. 
</P>
<P>
	More fundraising is needed for the school to compete, said board  
of trustees chairman Lawrence Ramer. 
</P>
<P>
	The trustees also reaffirmed Lafayette's policy of providing  
financial aid to student-athletes based solely on need. 
</P>
<P>
	Lafayette trustees authorized a study of the college's athletic  
program last October after the athletic department expressed 
concern that more money was needed to maintain the teams. Only five 
of Lafayette's 23 varsity teams had winning records last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The athletic department recommended dropping four varsity  
sports. A faculty committee favored dropping to a lower division 
but said, ``If a varsity sport needs to be sacrificed to support 
other varsity programs, the logical choice is football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lafayette, one of the smallest Division I schools with only  
2,200 students, spends more per student on its varsity programs 
than any of its Patriot League competitors. But most of its 
athletic funding comes from tuition, and it can't keep up with the 
overall spending of other schools. 
</P>
<P>
	College president Arthur Rothkopf received hundreds of letters  
from alumni, students and parents after suggesting the review last 
fall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
