<DOCNO> APW19990116.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Statement by White House Counsel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Text of White House Special Counsel Gregory Craig's statement  
following the House managers' presentation during the Senate 
impeachment trial of President Clinton, as transcribed by Federal 
Document Clearing House: 
</P>
<P>
	The 13 House Republican prosecutors have the constitutional  
burden to prove their case that the president of the United States 
should be removed from office. 
</P>
<P>
	After three uninterrupted days of presenting that case, they  
have failed to meet their burden. 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing, nothing in any of the presentations, nothing in the  
five-volume, 60,000 page record, nothing in the testimony of at 
least 100 witnesses has proven their case. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Republicans' case ends as it began, an  
unsubstantiated, circumstantial case that does not meet the 
constitutional standard to remove the president from office. That 
standard is clear. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike federal judges, who are appointed for life and who serve  
during good behavior, our president is elected by all the people 
and should only be removed for the most grave offenses against the 
Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	The simple truth is that the House Republican prosecutors failed  
to demonstrate that the will and interest of the American people 
would be served by nullifying the results of a national election. 
</P>
<P>
	Next week, on behalf of the president, we will present a strong,  
vigorous defense based on the facts, the law and the Constitution. 
And we look forward to the day when all of us can return to the 
important business of the American people. 
</P>
<P>
	Thank you very much.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hyde: Presidency Could Be Damaged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With a final flourish, House prosecutors  
demanded President Clinton's removal from office Saturday, telling 
a hushed audience of senators that otherwise the presidency itself 
may be ``deeply and perhaps permanently damaged.'' Senate leaders 
sparred over the issue of witnesses at the historic impeachment 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``Morally serious men and women can imagine circumstances at the  
far edge of the morally permissible'' in which a president could 
shade the truth for the good of the nation, said white-haired Rep. 
Henry Hyde, the lead prosecutor summing up three days of opening 
arguments. 
</P>
<P>
	``But under oath, for a private pleasure?'' he asked.  
</P>
<P>
	It was a question that cut to the core of the case, allegations  
that Clinton committed perjury and obstructed justice in an attempt 
to conceal his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Moments after Hyde concluded the prosecution's presentation,  
Clinton attorney Gregory Craig said the president's legal team 
would be ready with a ``strong vigorous defense, based on the 
facts, the law and the Constitution'' when the trial resumes on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate officials estimate that 1,500 people have stood in line  
each day to witness a few minutes of the drama. The trial, with 
Chief Justice William Rehnquist presiding, is the first such 
presidential impeachment proceeding since 1868. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyde addressed the trial and a nationwide television audience as  
Clinton labored over a speech of a different variety -- the State of 
the Union address he will deliver next Tuesday evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the three-day presentation by the House Republicans,  
there was little, if any, evidence that Clinton's Democratic 
support had eroded. 
</P>
<P>
	``Based on the current record, they (House prosecutors) are not  
going to win this trial,'' said Democratic Sen. Robert Torricelli 
of New Jersey. ``They need somebody to come before the Senate and 
give unexpected testimony or to commit a mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And one Republican, Vermont Sen. James Jeffords, sounded  
skeptical of the case. ``If you say lying about a non-crime (an 
affair) can be converted into a high crime by the way you handle 
it, that sets a pretty low standard for me,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It takes a two-thirds votes to convict a president and remove  
him from office. Republicans hold a 55-45 majority, so even if all 
GOP senators vote against Clinton, a dozen Democratic votes would 
be required to strip the nation's 42nd president of his powerful 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the House wrapped up its case, the Senate's  
Democratic and Republican leaders were maneuvering for advantage on 
the witness issue, which threatened an outbreak of partisan 
hostilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Majority Leader Trent Lott released a letter he had dispatched  
to the Democratic leader on Friday night, suggesting creation of a 
bipartisan group of senators that could ``save us time and trouble 
in the days ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott added that he knew the White House had been in contact with  
the Democrats, and he added it would be proper if he joined in any 
future conversations with the president's team. 
</P>
<P>
	In reply, Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle declined the  
invitation for a bipartisan group. ``It is my hope that such 
arrangements will ultimately prove unnecessary,'' he wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Republican favor granting the House's request to call  
witnesses; many -- but not all -- Democrats oppose it. 
</P>
<P>
	That issue won't be settled for at least another week, although  
many Republicans and Democrats say they expect the GOP to insist, 
at a minimum, on depositions of such possible witnesses as Ms. 
Lewinsky, presidential friend Vernon Jordan and Oval Office 
secretary Betty Currie. 
</P>
<P>
	It fell to Hyde, known in the House for his flashes of  
eloquence, to close. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of us have been called Clinton haters,'' he said. ``This  
is not a question of who we hate, this is a question of what we 
love ... the rule of law, equal justice before the law and honor in 
our public life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Illinois Republican noted proposed resolutions of censure  
that would sharply criticize Clinton for violating the people's 
trust. And he said if senators believed such allegations and yet 
voted to acquit the chief executive, ``the office of the presidency 
has been deeply, and perhaps permanently, damaged.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By his actions, Hyde said, Clinton had ``broken his covenant of  
trust with the American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We must never tolerate one law for the ruler and another for  
the ruled, he said. ``If we do, we break faith with our ancestors 
from Bunker Hill, Lexington and Concord to ... Desert Storm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other Republicans were scathing, folksy and serious by turn as  
they wrapped up their case. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Steve Buyer, R-Ind., derided Clinton for mounting a  
``so-what'' defense against the charges. ``The facts are stubborn. 
President Clinton lied, under oath. President Clinton committed 
perjury, repeatedly, willfully, premeditatedly. President Clinton 
obstructed justice, by tampering with evidence and witnesses,'' he 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Lindsey Graham of South Carolina, unlike most House  
prosecutors, paced the area behind the podium, speaking in a soft 
Southern drawl. ``I'll try to get you out so we can all have some 
lunch,'' he said in one momentary aside. 
</P>
<P>
	And Rep. Charles Canady of Florida said the Senate should not  
allow a president who has ``made himself a notorious example of 
lawlessness to remain in office.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 06:12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Jan. 16, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors To Wrap Up Opening Phase  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The impeachment trial of President Clinton  
resumes at 10 a.m. EST today with House prosecutors expected to 
wrap up their opening arguments. The lead prosecutor, House 
Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., is expected to 
deliver a summation. Prosecutors are trying to show that lying 
under oath and obstruction of justice, the crimes of which Clinton 
is accused, meet the Constitution's ``high crimes and 
misdemeanors'' standard for removal. Clinton's lawyers, who cannot 
interrupt the House presentation, sat quietly during the arguments, 
waiting for their turn next Tuesday. 

</P>
<P>
	Northeast, Midwest Seek Thaw  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Many in the Northeast and Midwest are hoping  
for a thaw today after winter storms lashed the region Thursday and 
yesterday with every permutation of precipitation -- snow, sleet, 
rain and ice. Roofs, especially, were starting to feel the strain 
after nearly 3 feet of snow piled up in some places. Temperatures 
in the region were expected to rise into the 40s and possibly 50s 
today and stay there through Tuesday, the National Weather Service 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Power Outage Disrupts Flights  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A power outage at the Federal Aviation  
Administration's regional air traffic control center disrupted air 
travel throughout the Northwest and delayed flights for about 8,000 
passengers. The outage and the failure of a backup generator lasted 
about 35 minutes yesterday when controllers lost radar and radio 
communications. The FAA halted all plane departures in the region 
until the problem was fixed, which delayed more than 8,000 
passengers, some for several hours. No safety problems were 
reported, officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	Dozens Found Massacred in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	RACAK, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The bodies of dozens of men were found  
scattered on a hillside and in ravines in southern Kosovo today, 
many of them mutilated, the day after a fierce attack by Serb 
forces on ethnic Albanian villages. Reporters counted at least 35 
bodies. Reporters and international verifiers were prevented on 
Friday from reaching the besieged area around the village of Racak, 
where the Kosovo Liberation Army rebels said at least 46 were 
killed, including eight guerrillas. Some had their eyes gouged out 
or heads smashed in, and one man lay decapitated in the courtyard 
of his compound. All wore civilian clothing, and many were older 
men. Verifiers said many had been shot at close range. 

</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris Starts Farmers' Fund  
</P>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Philip Morris will contribute $300 million  
to a trust fund to help tobacco farmers offset losses stemming from 
a declining demand for their product. In a letter obtained 
yesterday by The Associated Press, the company said it would put 
the money into the fund regardless of whether other tobacco 
companies decide to participate. Philip Morris would make 
additional payments over the next nine years if the three other 
companies -- R.J. Reynolds, Brown &AMP; Williamson and Lorillard -- 
decide to contribute. Eventually, the fund could grow to $5.15 
billion. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Makes Little Progress on Iraq  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council has made little  
progress on Iraq and may be more divided than ever after a week of 
discussing whether to resume weapons inspections. Council members 
say they are pleased and even encouraged that they are finally 
discussing Iraq and have proposals in hand a month after the 
U.S.-British airstrikes ended U.N. oversight of Baghdad's weapons 
programs. The key question is whether to abandon efforts to disarm 
Iraq or keep trying in the face of Baghdad's decision to never 
again allow U.N. weapons inspections. France and Russia subscribe 
to the former, but the United States and Britain insist that the 
council follow resolutions requiring inspectors to certify that 
Iraq has destroyed all its banned weapons. 

</P>
<P>
	Orioles' Angelos Arrives in Cuba  
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- A delegation that included Baltimore Orioles owner  
Peter Angelos arrived last night for weekend meetings with 
officials to work out the rules for possible exhibition games in 
Baltimore and Cuba. ``We appreciate the hospitality of the Cuban 
government and our own government's support of the two games,'' 
Angelos said. President Clinton announced he would let the Orioles 
play a Cuban team as part of a plan to increase relations between 
the countries while maintaining the U.S. economic embargo. 

</P>
<P>
	Tyson Returns to Ring  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Nineteen months after he bit a chunk off  
Evander Holyfield's ears, Mike Tyson returns to the ring. Tyson 
begins his second comeback from an enforced ring absence when he 
meets Francois Botha in a scheduled 10-round fight tonight. The 
32-year-old Tyson, who weighed in Thursday at 223 pounds is a 6-1 
favorite against Botha, who briefly held the IBF title and has lost 
once in his career. Botha has 24 knockouts, but is not known for 
his punching power. He holds a size advantage of about three inches 
over Tyson and outweighs him by 10 pounds. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 13:21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pak Signs 3-Year Contract With IMG  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Maybe now Se Ri Pak will be able to  
concentrate only on golf. 
</P>
<P>
	After a sensational season on the course and a muddled situation  
outside the ropes, Pak signed a contract with International 
Management Group, the same agency that represents Tiger Woods, 
David Duval and Annika Sorenstam. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract was signed Thursday night over dinner. Pak had been  
scheduled to hear a last-ditch offer from Cornerstone Sports, but 
signed with IMG before the latter meeting was held. 
</P>
<P>
	IMG declined comment, but the deal was confirmed Friday by  
family adviser Yeong Shin by Samsung, Pak's corporate sponsor. 
</P>
<P>
	``IMG will handle everything,'' said Shin, as he and her father,  
Jun-Chul Pak, watched her struggle to a 2-over 74 in the first 
round of the HealthSouth Inaugural. 
</P>
<P>
	Pak, who became the youngest winner of the U.S. Women's Open and  
the first rookie in 14 years to win two majors, had been shopping 
for a management firm since last month, when Samsung agreed to give 
up management of the South Korean star. 
</P>
<P>
	Shin said he expects endorsement contracts to follow shortly.  
Pak has played the Callaway Big Bertha irons and the Maxfli 
Revolution ball, although she did not have deals with any other 
company except Samsung. 
</P>
<P>
	``Samsung will still be primary sponsor,'' Shin said. ``She will  
still have Samsung on the hat and Astra on the shirt. But IMG will 
negotiate with Callaway and for other equipment endorsements.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope the systematic and scientific management through IMG  
will help Pak remain a top-notch player,'' Samsung spokesman Ahn 
Ho-moon said from South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	IMG will split 30 percent of the profits with Samsung. Pak will  
receive the remaining 70 percent, Samsung officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Samsung, the Korean electronics magnate, signed Pak to a 10-year  
contract in 1996, then sent her to the United States to work with 
swing coach David Leadbetter. 
</P>
<P>
	She tied for first in the LPGA qualifying school, then  
challenged Sorenstam as the top player in the world with the most 
remarkable rookie season on the LPGA Tour since Nancy Lopez in 
1978. She was voted AP Female Athlete of the Year, and was voted 
player of the year by the Golf Writers Association of America. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with winning the U.S. Open in a 20-hole playoff and the  
LPGA Championship, Pak won two other tournaments -- all in a 10-week 
stretch -- and set two scoring records in one of them. 
</P>
<P>
	But off the course, her life was far from smooth.  
</P>
<P>
	Leadbetter said she was playing too much. Pak played six  
straight tournaments on two occasions late in the year and 
complained of a sore shoulder and fatigue. She also was 
hospitalized for fatigue during her celebrated homecoming to South 
Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	When the season ended, Pak fired manager Steven Kil, rehired him  
and fired him again -- all within two weeks. She also ditched 
Leadbetter, decided to go back to him, then received notice that he 
was leaving her. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to find very strong people to take care of everything --  
interviews, schedule, practice and time for me to relax,'' Pak said 
recently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 13:21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
