<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5:30 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Jan. 16, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	40 Bodies Seen After Kosovo Fight  
</P>
<P>
	RACAK, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The bodies of up to 40 people, many of  
them mutilated, were found in a southern Kosovo village today, the 
day after Serb forces launched a fierce assault on the area. 
Reporters and international verifiers who were prevented from 
reaching the village of Racak the previous day arrived today and 
saw the bodies scattered on a hillside. Some had their eyes gouged 
out or their heads bashed in, and one man lay decapitated. 

</P>
<P>
	Power Outage Disrupts Flights  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A power outage at the Federal Aviation  
Administration's regional air traffic control center disrupted air 
travel throughout the Northwest and delayed flights for about 8,000 
passengers. The outage and the failure of a backup generator lasted 
about 35 minutes yesterday when controllers lost radar and radio 
communications. The FAA halted all plane departures in the region 
until the problem was fixed, which delayed more than 8,000 
passengers, some for several hours. No safety problems were 
reported, officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	Ice, Rain Glaze the East  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Snow and freezing rain put a hard-shell finish  
on the East yesterday, causing deadly highway accidents, backing up 
airline flights and knocking out power to thousands of people. The 
snow that blanketed the Northeast on Thursday was topped by 
freezing rain early yesterday, creating a slick coating over much 
of the region during the morning rush hour. As the day wore on and 
temperatures climbed out of the teens, people found themselves 
slogging through slush and high water. At least 10 people died 
since Wednesday in traffic accidents in West Virginia, Maryland, 
Massachusetts and Maine that were blamed on rain, snow and ice. 

</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors Wrap Up Opening Phase  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After alleging that William Jefferson Clinton  
``violated the laws of this land,'' prosecutors at the president's 
impeachment trial are set to argue that his conduct amounted to 
``high crimes and misdemeanors'' warranting his removal. Continuing 
the proceedings into the weekend, senators were anxious to stay on 
schedule for the crucial decision on whether to invite the 
president to testify and summon several of his close aides and 
associates as witnesses. Before the ``court'' of the Senate, the 
House ``managers'' were presenting their third and final day of 
opening arguments today. 

</P>
<P>
	Marine Pilot Has One Charge Dropped  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A judge yesterday dismissed negligent  
homicide charges against a Marine pilot in the Italian ski gondola 
tragedy that killed 20 people -- but the aviator still faces more 
serious charges. The pilot, Capt. Richard Ashby, 31, of Mission 
Viejo, Calif., will be court-martialed next month on the graver 
charges of involuntary manslaughter, as well as several lesser 
charges. The prosecutors' decision to seek dismissal of the 
negligent homicide charges was viewed as a strategic move -- 
possibly aimed at forcing jurors to convict Ashby on more serious 
charges at his court-martial next month. 

</P>
<P>
	Navy Recruiting More Non-Graduates  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Navy, faced with a worrisome 22,000 job  
vacancies, has decided to start accepting more recruits who have 
not earned a high school diploma. In announcing the decision 
yesterday, Navy Secretary Richard Danzig said it was among a series 
of moves intended to improve the Navy's war preparedness and raise 
morale. The job gap has meant that some sailors among the 372,000 
on active duty are forced to fill positions outside their own 
specialty or to do double duty, he said of the 22,000 unfilled 
jobs, 18,000 are aboard ships at sea. 

</P>
<P>
	FDA Approves New Leg Drug  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Food and Drug Administration approved the  
first drug in 15 years to help several million Americans with a 
circulatory disorder so painful it inhibits walking. But the 
approval of Pletal yesterday for the painful leg syndrome known as 
intermittent claudication, the Latin word for limping, came amid 
criticism that the drug may endanger certain heart patients. The 
disorder occurs in people, mostly the elderly, who have poor blood 
circulation in their legs. 

</P>
<P>
	Blackhawks Beat Rangers 3-1  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mike Maneluk scored on a breakaway and Jocelyn  
Thibault stopped 31 shots to snap the Chicago Blackhawks' 
seven-game winless streak with a 3-1 victory over the New York 
Rangers last night. Maneluk took advantage of a bad line change by 
New York to skate in alone on goalie Mike Richter and beat him at 
4:48 of the third period with a wrist shot from 12 feet for his 
fifth goal of the season. That broke a 1-1 tie and gave the 
Blackhawks only their fourth victory in 21 road games this season. 
Tony Amonte added an empty-net goal for Chicago, his 24th, with 
three seconds left. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
</P>
</TEXT>
