<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 19 Senators on Sunday Talk Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- No need to keep feeling sorry for senators  
forced to sit in virtual silence during the Senate's impeachment 
trial of President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly one-fifth of the Senate -- 19 to be exact -- was scheduled  
to appear Sunday on national television news programs. And this 
despite an admonition by Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, 
R-Miss., earlier this week that senators should refrain from 
publicly discussing the merits of the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being impartial, which is the oath we took, doesn't mean not  
having an opinion,'' said Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who plans 
to appear on ``Fox News Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schumer has been among several senators who after each session  
of the Senate trial have been willing to discuss the day's events 
with reporters. Though difficult to quantify, senators seem to have 
split roughly evenly between those who avoid commenting to 
journalists and those who do so. 
</P>
<P>
	Those like Schumer who have talked publicly about the trial say  
their status is different from that of regular jurors, in part 
because it includes politics. Unlike most jurors, senators are 
being lobbied by constituents about the trial, and many of them 
have campaigned either for or against Clinton over the years. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, many of them feel it is proper to talk about the case --  
within limits. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a certain amount of powder that should be kept dry,''  
said Sen. Tim Johnson, D-S.D., who said he might appear on ``Larry 
King Live'' on CNN. ``It's proper to talk about the process, but I 
don't want to make declarations about how I'll vote prior to a 
given vote.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others, however, walk briskly past reporters when they are  
approached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made the decision at the very outset that I wouldn't discuss  
anything,'' said Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about his 19 colleagues slated to appear on the talk  
shows, he said: ``You will note that I'm not one of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 19 who were scheduled for appearances on Sunday, 10 were  
Democrats and nine were Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Eds: The 19 are: Sens. Robert Bennett, R-Utah; Barbara Boxer,  
D-Calif.; Larry Craig, R-Idaho; Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.; Pete 
Domenici, R-N.M.; Byron Dorgan, D-N.D.; Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.; 
Phil Gramm, R-Texas; Tom Harkin, D-Iowa; Orrin Hatch, R-Utah; Kay 
Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas; James Inhofe, R-Okla.; John Kerry, 
D-Mass.; Jon Kyl, R-Ariz.; Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.; Mitch McConnell, 
R-Ky.; Schumer; Robert Torricelli, D-N.J.; and Paul Wellstone, 
D-Minn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
