<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miami's Avery Hurt by Late Nights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVIE, Fla. (AP) -- Miami Dolphins running back John Avery  
acknowledges that part of the reason for his rookie struggles was 
his inability to stay awake during team meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	The reason: Staying up too late playing video games.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think they have some program for dealing with it, don't  
they? ... I think I have it handled now,'' Avery said in the 
Sun-Sentinel of Fort Lauderdale on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, offensive coordinator Kippy Brown became so  
exasperated with Avery that he kicked the rookie out of a meeting. 
That was in the week leading up to Miami's wild-card playoff game 
against Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	Avery was limited to one carry in the Dolphins' two playoff  
games, working almost exclusively as a kickoff returner. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a team situation that I'm not going to get into,''  
Brown said, refusing further comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Avery said: ``It only happened a couple of times, but he was  
mad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Avery, Miami's first-round draft pick, rushed for 503 yards on  
143 carries and had two rushing touchdowns. The former Mississippi 
standout also caught 10 passes for 67 yards and one touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jimmy Johnson would not comment on Avery's inopportune  
naps. He was critical early this season of the running back's 
tendency to try to juke defenders rather than hitting the hole, but 
later said Avery's performance was satisfactory for a rookie. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson has dealt with the problem in different ways in the  
past. When he coached the Dallas Cowboys, Johnson cut linebacker 
John Roper for falling asleep. Then again, Johnson also has let 
other players slide for the same crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``He told us in training camp that guys fall asleep,'' Avery  
said. ``There was that one guy he cut. Then he said Troy Aikman 
fell asleep one time. He said, 'You think I'm going to cut Troy 
Aikman?''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:09:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutors Deride Clinton Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Wrapping up their opening arguments, House  
prosecutors today launched a blistering attack on what they called 
President Clinton's ``so-what'' defense. They told senators he 
should be removed from office because he ``abused the trust placed 
upon him by the American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott asked Democrats to  
meet to discuss the possibility of calling witnesses later in the 
trial, but he got a cool response from Senate Democratic Leader Tom 
Daschle. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott suggested in a letter to Daschle that ``a bipartisan group  
of senators could anticipate and help resolve in advance any 
complications'' brought about by witness testimony. ``We should 
consider safeguards now so that testimony could begin as soon as 
fairness allowed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Daschle said such a move would violate the Senate's previous  
agreement, which calls for the witness question to be settled later 
in the process. ``I agree that the prospect of witness testimony 
poses a number of troubling considerations that we would be forced 
to confront,'' Daschle wrote. ``It is my hope that such 
arrangements will ultimately prove unnecessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The public galleries were full again on a chilly Saturday  
morning as the House prosecutors opened their final arguments, 
seeking to show that perjury before a grand jury and obstruction of 
justice are offenses that meet the impeachment standard. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our Constitution, and the American people, entrust to the  
president singular responsibility for enforcing the rule of law. 
Perjury and obstruction of justice strike at the heart of the rule 
of law,'' Rep. Steve Buyer, R-Ind., told a hushed Senate chamber. 
</P>
<P>
	``A president who has committed these crimes has plainly and  
directly violated his most important executive duty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., his Southern tones echoing in the  
chamber, sought to put a human face to a case dominated by legal 
distinctions. He told senators a high crime was simply ``if a high 
person hurts a person of low means'' and that Clinton's effort to 
``fix this case'' when sued by Paula Jones met that standard. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the case was one of ``serious offenses colored by sex  
and there is absolutely no way to get around that. And I know it is 
uncomfortable to listen to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graham also cautioned senators that if they convict Clinton they  
would put a ``burden'' on the next president: ``Don't lie under 
oath when you are a defendant in a lawsuit against an average 
citizen. Have the courage to apply the law in a fair manner to 
yourself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just as Saturday's proceedings got under way, Clinton entered  
the Oval Office to applause from guests invited to his weekly radio 
broadcast. He exhorted Americans to observe Martin Luther King Jr. 
Day as a day of community service, and then settled down with aides 
to rehearse his upcoming State of the Union address. He told 
Democrats at a party gala late Friday night that he was 
``determined to make the most of the days ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., another of the prosecutors,  
reminded senators they have impeached and removed federal judges 
for perjury. ``The Senate should not establish a lower standard of 
integrity for the president than the standard it has already 
established for federal judges,'' Canady argued in prepared 
remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutors attacked the defenses erected by the Clinton  
legal team, saying concealing his affair with Monica Lewinsky from 
a court was public, not private, conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	``Contrary to the claims of the president's lawyers, there is  
not a bright line separating official misconduct by a president 
from other misconduct of which the president is guilty,'' Canady 
argued. 
</P>
<P>
	Buyer said, ``I'm not offended by the 'so what' defense. If that  
is all you have then try it.'' He said presidential lawyers seemed 
to feel their only chance was to ``attack the prosecutor and 
attempt to confuse those who sit in judgment. 
</P>
<P>
	``The House is prepared to establish that the president, William  
Jefferson Clinton, willfully and repeatedly violated the rule of 
law and abused the trust placed upon him by the American people,'' 
Buyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	He drew a sharp distinction between a man trying to hide an  
extramarital affair from his wife and what Clinton is accused of 
doing in hiding his actions from the court in the Jones lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Continuing the proceedings into the weekend, senators were  
anxious to stay on schedule for the crucial decision on whether to 
invite the president to testify and whether to summon several of 
his close aides and associates as witnesses. House prosecutors have 
relentlessly pressed for permission to call witnesses later in the 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House already has said Clinton would not testify.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's lawyers, who cannot interrupt the House presentation  
to object, sat quietly at the prosecution table during the 
arguments, waiting for their turn Tuesday. But White House special 
counsel Gregory Craig launched a brief salvo outside the Senate 
chamber, saying prosecutors wanted to ``expand and extend this 
proceeding for one reason: They do not have a case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is charged under two articles of impeachment with  
perjury and obstruction of justice in the first presidential 
impeachment trial since the Andrew Johnson case in 1868. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-thirds, or 67 of the 100 senators, most vote for conviction  
to remove the president from office, and there are no indications 
that any Democrats would vote against the president. Twelve 
Democrats would have to join the 55 Republicans in order to remove 
Clinton from office if the GOP stayed united. 
</P>
<P>
	There was a first moment of surprise Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, suddenly objected to the House  
prosecutors' ``continued use of the word 'jurors''' to describe 
senators, who have a multipurpose role that also includes making 
trial decisions reserved for lawyers and judges in regular 
courtroom proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	Rehnquist, who has had little to do as presiding officer, made  
his first ruling of the trial: ``The objection is well taken. The 
Senate is not simply a jury but a court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., who had just told the Senate that Clinton  
violated perjury and obstruction of justice statutes, quickly 
concluded his remarks without referring to the word ``jurors,'' as 
he had done several times previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
