<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 01:05:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 62 Players File for Arbitration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Only 62 players filed for salary arbitration this year, the  
second-lowest total in 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	For the World Series champion New York Yankees, the total isn't  
significant. Derek Jeter, Andy Pettitte and Mariano Rivera filed, 
meaning their payroll will grow to about $80 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas pitchers Rick Helling and Aaron Sele also were among those  
who filed Friday. Barring settlements, they'll exchange figures 
with their teams Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1979, when 40 players filed, the only year fewer players  
went to arbitration was 1995. Following the 232-day strike, just 56 
players filed and only eight had hearings. 
</P>
<P>
	Most players who file settle before their cases are heard. Just  
eight were decided by arbitrators last year, with owners winning 
five. 
</P>
<P>
	Three Los Angeles Dodgers players settled before the deadline,  
with pitcher Carlos Perez getting a $15.5 million, three-year 
contract. Ismael Valdes ($4,275,000) and outfielder Todd 
Hollandsworth ($850,000) got one-year deals. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis agreed to a $1.8 million, two-year contract with  
left-hander Lance Painter and a $550,000, one-year contract with 
right-hander Alan Benes. 
</P>
<P>
	Reliever Curtis Leskanic got a $2.6 million, two-year deal with  
Colorado, and Albie Lopez, another reliever, agreed to a $1.35 
million, two-year contract with Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Infielder David Bell agreed to a two-year contract with Seattle  
that is worth $1,775,000, and outfielder Roger Cedeno and the New 
York Mets agreed to a $487,500, one-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati right-hander Jason Bere became the first of the  
players who filed to settle, agreeing to a $1.2 million, one-year 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixty-one players filed Friday and joined Toronto first baseman  
Carlos Delgado, who filed Thursday. Because of Monday's Martin 
Luther King holiday, all will exchange numbers Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets and the Houston Astros had the most players filing, six  
each, followed by the Rangers with five. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the decrease in the overall total -- a record 161 were in  
arbitration in 1990 and the total topped 100 from 1986 through 1993 
-- is due to clubs releasing and threatening to release marginal 
players rather than arbitrate with them. As a result, more than 
half of the players who filed -- 33 -- were eligible for arbitration 
for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them are seven of the so-called ``Super Twos,'' those with  
2-3 years of major league service who became eligible for 
arbitration under the 1990 lockout settlement. Among them are 
Helling, Houston closer Billy Wagner, St. Louis shortstop Edgar 
Renteria and Montreal starter Dustin Hermanson, all set to receive 
huge raises. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the 1996 collective bargaining agreement, 75 percent  
of cases will be scheduled for three-man arbitration panels and 25 
percent for single arbitrators. 
</P>
<P>
	In a new twist, the labor lawyers in the commissioner's office  
have asked teams to confer with them before settling arbitration 
cases to give them a chance to argue against agreements they think 
are too high. But the process isn't mandatory and some clubs won't 
follow it. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, two free agents found new teams Friday. Pitcher Mike  
Mohler and St. Louis agreed to a one-year contract, while infielder 
Luis Rivera and Anaheim agreed to a minor league deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990116.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:10:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Graham Uses Folksy Ways in Speech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Strolling around the well of the Senate, South  
Carolina's Lindsey Graham used a folksy approach to urge a 
``cleansing'' of the presidency through removal of President 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham's presentation Saturday was remarkable both for his  
relaxed style and for his message. Calling himself a ``son of the 
South'' who grew up amid racial segregation, Graham said that 
Clinton cannot be a civil rights champion if he is guilty of 
perjury in a sexual harassment lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe he's been an articulate spokesman for civil rights  
for our citizens,'' Graham told the Senate. ``When those rights had 
to be applied to him, he failed miserably.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graham, 43, was swept into office during the 1994 Republican  
capture of Congress. Before the impeachment drama, he was best 
known for his role in the attempted coup than nearly ousted Newt 
Gingrich as House speaker in 1997. He is a vocal advocate of term 
limits. 
</P>
<P>
	He bucked the other Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee  
when he voted against one of the four articles of impeachment 
originally lodged against Clinton -- the one alleging perjury in the 
Paula Jones case. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham served as a judge advocate in the Air Force and is a  
major in the South Carolina Air National Guard. 
</P>
<P>
	During Saturday's arguments, he used a clip-on microphone so he  
could move away from the lectern and -- unlike most of his House 
colleagues -- he used only notes to deliver his speech. 
</P>
<P>
	He made a clear attempt to be less formal: ``I'll try to get you  
out so we can all have some lunch,'' Graham said at one point. And 
later: ``If this is a football game, we're almost to halftime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Graham was deadly serious in his message, which focused on  
past impeachment trials of federal judges and how the Senate had 
determined that wrongful conduct outside official duties could be 
grounds for removal from office. 
</P>
<P>
	``Impeachment is about cleansing the office. Impeachment is  
about restoring honor and integrity,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham also referred to Clinton's continuing popularity, saying  
senators must trust that people would believe they did the proper 
thing if the president were removed. 
</P>
<P>
	``They will trust you. This is a cynical age, but I'm an  
optimist that no matter what you do, this country will get up and 
go to work the next day and we'll feel good,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
