<DOCNO> APW19990116.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:09:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutors Wrap Up Opening Phase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After alleging that William Jefferson Clinton  
``violated the laws of this land,'' prosecutors at the president's 
impeachment trial are set to argue that his conduct amounted to 
``high crimes and misdemeanors'' warranting his removal. 
</P>
<P>
	Continuing the proceedings into the weekend, senators were  
anxious to stay on schedule for the crucial decision on whether to 
invite the president to testify and summon several of his close 
aides and associates as witnesses. House prosecutors have 
relentlessly pressed for permission to call witnesses later in the 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's our purpose. We try,'' House Judiciary Committee  
Chairman Henry Hyde, the lead prosecutor, said today before the 
House managers were presenting their third and final day of opening 
arguments. 
</P>
<P>
	Those lawmakers-turned-prosecutors were prepared to contend that  
lying under oath and obstruction of justice meet the Constitution's 
standard for removal. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyde, R-Ill., was expected to deliver a summation.  
</P>
<P>
	As Chief Justice William Rehnquist, the presiding officer,  
peered down at the Senate from his elevated dais Friday, Rep. Bill 
McCollum, R-Fla. argued that the president, his friend Vernon 
Jordan, his secretary Betty Currie and at least two staff aides 
should testify because their testimony conflicts with that of 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``Time and again somebody is not telling the truth and time and  
again an analysis of ... all the testimony together with common 
sense says it's the president who is not telling the truth,'' 
McCollum said. ``But if you have serious doubts about the 
truthfulness'' of key witnesses, he said, they should appear in 
person. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House already has said Clinton would not testify.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's lawyers, who cannot interrupt the House presentation  
to object, sat quietly at the prosecution table during the 
arguments, waiting for their turn Tuesday. But White House special 
counsel Gregory Craig launched a brief salvo outside the Senate 
chamber, saying prosecutors wanted to ``expand and extend this 
proceeding for one reason: They do not have a case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is charged under two articles of impeachment with  
perjury and obstruction of justice in the first presidential 
impeachment trial since the Andrew Johnson case in 1868. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-thirds, or 67 of the 100 senators, most vote for conviction  
to remove the president from office, and there are no indications 
that any Democrats would vote against the president. Twelve 
Democrats would have to join the 55 Republicans in order to remove 
Clinton from office if the GOP stayed united. 
</P>
<P>
	The opening argument phase of the trial is governed by a  
bipartisan agreement that postpones the question of witnesses for 
at least another week. But, as Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., 
acknowledged, ``there may be very well'' a party-line vote on the 
witness question. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the public were in line on an icy Washington morning  
Friday for 50 gallery seats filled on a rotating basis. Those there 
late Friday afternoon saw the only fleeting moment of surprise in a 
trial governed mostly by 19th century rules that require senators 
to remain silent ``on pain of imprisonment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, suddenly objected to the House  
prosecutors' ``continued use of the word 'jurors''' to describe 
senators, who have a multipurpose role that also includes making 
trial decisions reserved for lawyers and judges in regular 
courtroom proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	Rehnquist, who has had little to do as presiding officer, made  
his first ruling of the trial: ``The objection is well taken. The 
Senate is not simply a jury but a court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., who had just told the Senate that Clinton  
violated perjury and obstruction of justice statutes, quickly 
concluded his remarks without referring to the word ``jurors,'' as 
he had done several times previously. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the interruption, Barr asked the Senate to conclude  
``that William Jefferson Clinton in fact and under the law, 
violated his oath and violated the laws of this land, and convict 
him on both articles of impeachment ....'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., another prosecutor, likewise argued  
that Clinton committed federal crimes, even though impeachable acts 
need not be criminal offenses. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Clinton ``turned the judicial system on its head for his  
own legal and political gain. This case is about perjury, multiple 
obstructions of justice, false and misleading statements and 
witness tampering, all committed or orchestrated by the 
president.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
